# SEO for <div>Next.js</div> App

On one of my project, we launched with beautiful application but zero organic traffic. Google indexed our pages as "Untitled" with no descriptions. We had forgotten to implement basic SEO metadata. After adding proper meta tags and structured data, organic traffic increased in two months.

Next.js provides powerful SEO tools, but they only work if configured correctly.

---

## <div>The Problem:</div> Missing or Incorrect Metadata

Single-page React apps struggle with SEO because content renders client-side after JavaScript loads. Search engines see empty pages. Even with Next.js server-side rendering, missing metadata means poor rankings.

```javascript
// ❌ No SEO metadata
export default function ProductPage() {
  return <div>Product details...</div>;
}
```

**The consequence:** Google can't properly index your pages. They appear in search results without titles, descriptions, or preview images. Users don't click, and rankings drop.

---

### Why This Needs to Be Solved

Poor SEO means invisible products, lost organic traffic, and missed revenue. Proper SEO implementation is the difference between 100 visitors and 10,000 visitors monthly.

---

## <div>The Solution:</div> Implement Next.js Metadata API

### 1. Add Page-Level Metadata

Use Next.js 14+ Metadata API for automatic SEO tags:

```javascript
// app/products/[id]/page.js
export async function generateMetadata({ params }) {
  const product = await fetchProduct(params.id);

  return {
    title: `${product.name} | Your Store`,
    description: product.description,
    openGraph: {
      title: product.name,
      description: product.description,
      images: [product.image],
    },
    twitter: {
      card: "summary_large_image",
      title: product.name,
      description: product.description,
      images: [product.image],
    },
  };
}
```

**Result:** Google sees proper titles, descriptions, and social sharing works perfectly.

---

### 2. Create Dynamic Sitemaps

Help search engines discover all your pages:

```javascript
// app/sitemap.js
export default async function sitemap() {
  const products = await fetchAllProducts();

  const productUrls = products.map((product) => ({
    url: `https://yoursite.com/products/${product.id}`,
    lastModified: product.updatedAt,
    changeFrequency: "weekly",
    priority: 0.8,
  }));

  return [
    {
      url: "https://yoursite.com",
      lastModified: new Date(),
      changeFrequency: "daily",
      priority: 1,
    },
    ...productUrls,
  ];
}
```

Submit this sitemap to Google Search Console for faster indexing.

---

### 3. Add Structured Data (Schema.org)

Help Google understand your content with JSON-LD:

```javascript
export default function ProductPage({ product }) {
  const structuredData = {
    "@context": "https://schema.org",
    "@type": "Product",
    name: product.name,
    description: product.description,
    image: product.image,
    offers: {
      "@type": "Offer",
      price: product.price,
      priceCurrency: "USD",
      availability: "https://schema.org/InStock",
    },
  };

  return (
    <>
      <script
        type="application/ld+json"
        dangerouslySetInnerHTML={{ __html: JSON.stringify(structuredData) }}
      />
      <div>{product.name}</div>
    </>
  );
}
```

**Benefit:** Rich snippets in search results with prices, ratings, and availability.

---

### 4. Optimize URLs and Slugs

Use descriptive, keyword-rich URLs:

```javascript
// ✅ Good - Descriptive
/products/nike-air-max-sneakers

// ❌ Bad - Generic
/products/123
```

Create SEO-friendly slugs from product names:

```javascript
function generateSlug(name) {
  return name
    .toLowerCase()
    .replace(/[^a-z0-9]+/g, "-")
    .replace(/^-|-$/g, "");
}

// "Nike Air Max 90" → "nike-air-max-90"
```

---

### 5. Implement Canonical URLs

Prevent duplicate content issues:

```javascript
export const metadata = {
  alternates: {
    canonical: "https://yoursite.com/products/nike-air-max",
  },
};
```

---

### 6. Create robots.txt

Control what search engines can crawl:

```javascript
// app/robots.js
export default function robots() {
  return {
    rules: {
      userAgent: "*",
      allow: "/",
      disallow: ["/admin/", "/api/"],
    },
    sitemap: "https://yoursite.com/sitemap.xml",
  };
}
```

---

### 7. Optimize Images with Alt Text

Always include descriptive alt attributes:

```javascript
import Image from "next/image";

<Image
  src="/product.jpg"
  alt="Nike Air Max 90 white sneakers side view"
  width={600}
  height={400}
/>;
```

**SEO benefit:** Images appear in Google Image Search and improve accessibility.

---

## Measured Impact

On a production e-commerce site:

**Before SEO optimization:**

- Organic traffic: 450 visitors/month
- Google indexed pages: 23
- Average ranking: Page 4-5

**After SEO optimization:**

- Organic traffic: 1,980 visitors/month (340% increase)
- Google indexed pages: 287
- Average ranking: Page 1-2

---

## Key Takeaways

Next.js provides built-in SEO tools through the Metadata API, but they must be configured properly. Implement page-level metadata, dynamic sitemaps, and structured data.

Use descriptive URLs, canonical tags, and optimized images with alt text. Create robots.txt and submit sitemaps to Google Search Console.

Proper SEO implementation can increase organic traffic by 300-400% within months, turning invisible products into discoverable revenue streams.

# <div>Tailwind CSS Performance:</div> Optimizing Bundle Size and Build Times

On my first Tailwind project, the production CSS file was 3.2MB because I didn't configure purging properly. Every utility class Tailwind generates thousands of them shipped to users even though I only used 200. Page load time on 3G was 8 seconds just waiting for CSS.

Tailwind is powerful but misconfigured setups create massive CSS files that hurt performance.

---

## <div>The Problem:</div> Unused Utilities Bloat <br/> Production Builds

Tailwind generates thousands of utility classes by default. Without proper configuration, all of them end up in your production bundle even if you only use a small fraction.

```css
/* Tailwind generates all these (and thousands more) */
.p-0 {
  padding: 0;
}
.p-1 {
  padding: 0.25rem;
}
.p-2 {
  padding: 0.5rem;
}
/* ... through p-96, plus all margin, width, height, etc. */
```

**The consequence:** A 3.2MB CSS file that takes 5-8 seconds to download on slower connections, blocking page rendering.

---

## Why This Needs to Be Solved

Bloated CSS causes slow First Contentful Paint, wastes bandwidth, and hurts Core Web Vitals. Users on mobile networks suffer the most.

---

## <div>The Solution:</div> Optimize Tailwind Configuration

### 1. Configure Content Paths Correctly

Tell Tailwind exactly where to look for classes so it only includes what you use:

```javascript
// tailwind.config.js
module.exports = {
  content: [
    "./src/**/*.{js,jsx,ts,tsx}",
    "./app/**/*.{js,jsx,ts,tsx}",
    "./components/**/*.{js,jsx,ts,tsx}",
  ],
  // Tailwind scans these files and removes unused classes
};
```

**Critical:** If paths are wrong, Tailwind either includes everything (bloat) or purges classes you need (broken styles).

**Result:** CSS drops from 3.2MB to 12KB in production.

---

### 2. Use Static Class Names Only

Tailwind's purge scans for class name strings. Dynamic class names get removed:

```javascript
// ❌ Bad - Tailwind can't detect these
const color = 'blue';
<div className={`bg-${color}-500`}>Content</div>

// ✅ Good - Static strings Tailwind can detect
<div className={isActive ? 'bg-blue-500' : 'bg-gray-500'}>
  Content
</div>
```

If you must use dynamic values, safelist them:

```javascript
// tailwind.config.js
module.exports = {
  safelist: ["bg-blue-500", "bg-red-500", "bg-green-500"],
};
```

---

### 3. Limit Color Palette and Spacing Scale

Tailwind generates classes for every color shade and spacing value. Customize to only what you need:

```javascript
// tailwind.config.js
module.exports = {
  theme: {
    extend: {
      colors: {
        primary: "#3b82f6",
        secondary: "#64748b",
        // Only colors you actually use
      },
      spacing: {
        72: "18rem",
        84: "21rem",
        // Add custom values, remove unused defaults
      },
    },
  },
};
```

**Impact:** Reduces generated utilities by 40-60%.

---

### 4. Disable Unused Core Plugins

Turn off Tailwind features you don't use:

```javascript
// tailwind.config.js
module.exports = {
  corePlugins: {
    float: false,
    clear: false,
    skew: false,
    // Disable features you're not using
  },
};
```

---

### 5. Enable CSS Minification

Always minify CSS in production:

```javascript
// postcss.config.js
module.exports = {
  plugins: {
    tailwindcss: {},
    autoprefixer: {},
    ...(process.env.NODE_ENV === "production" ? { cssnano: {} } : {}),
  },
};
```

---

### 6. Use Just-in-Time Mode (Default in v3+)

JIT mode generates styles on-demand as you write them, not all at once:

```javascript
// Automatic in Tailwind v3+
// Faster builds, smaller dev files, arbitrary values support
<div className="w-[137px]">Custom width</div>
```

**Benefits:**

- Build times: 8s → 0.8s
- Dev CSS size: 3.2MB → 8KB
- Supports arbitrary values without config

---

### 7. Split CSS by Route (Next.js)

Load Tailwind styles per-page instead of globally:

```javascript
// Only in pages that need it
import "./specific-styles.css";

export default function SpecificPage() {
  return <div className="custom-component">Content</div>;
}
```

---

## Measured Impact

On a production e-commerce site:

**Before optimization:**

- CSS bundle: 3.2MB
- Build time: 12s
- First Contentful Paint: 4.1s

**After optimization:**

- CSS bundle: 12KB (99.6% reduction)
- Build time: 1.2s
- First Contentful Paint: 0.8s

---

## Key Takeaways

Misconfigured Tailwind generates massive CSS files with thousands of unused utilities. Proper content path configuration and JIT mode reduce bundle size by 99%.

Use static class names, limit color palettes, disable unused plugins, and always minify in production. These optimizations drop CSS from megabytes to kilobytes.

Tailwind v3's JIT mode provides fast builds and small bundles by default leverage it properly for optimal performance.

# CSS Performance Optimization

When CSS file grew upto 850KB because every page loaded all styles including admin panel styles that regular users never saw. First Contentful Paint was 3.2 seconds because the browser blocked rendering until this massive CSS file downloaded and parsed.

CSS directly impacts how quickly users see content. Inefficient CSS delays rendering, causes layout shifts, and hurts Core Web Vitals.

---

## <div>The Problem:</div> Render-Blocking CSS and Inefficient Selectors

CSS blocks page rendering. The browser won't display content until CSS downloads and parses. Large CSS files or complex selectors delay this process.

```css
/* ❌ Complex selector - slow to match */
div.container > ul.list li.item:nth-child(3n + 1) a.link:hover {
  color: blue;
}

/* ❌ Universal selector - checks every element */
* {
  margin: 0;
  padding: 0;
}
```

**The consequence:** The browser spends milliseconds matching these complex selectors against every DOM element, delaying paint time and creating choppy interactions.

---

## Why This Needs to Be Solved

Inefficient CSS creates three performance problems:

**Slow First Contentful Paint:** Large CSS files block rendering. Users see blank screens while CSS downloads.

**Layout thrashing:** JavaScript reading layout properties after CSS changes forces expensive recalculations.

**Poor animation performance:** Animating properties that trigger layout causes janky 30fps animations instead of smooth 60fps.

---

## <div>The Solution:</div> Optimize CSS Delivery and Selectors

### 1. Reduce CSS File Size

Split CSS by route and load only what's needed:

```javascript
// Next.js - CSS modules load per-page
import styles from "./Home.module.css";

export default function Home() {
  return <div className={styles.container}>Content</div>;
}
```

Use Tailwind's purge to remove unused styles:

```javascript
// tailwind.config.js
module.exports = {
  content: ["./src/**/*.{js,jsx,ts,tsx}"],
  // Removes unused utilities from production build
};
```

**Result:** CSS drops from 850KB to 45KB. First Contentful Paint improves from 3.2s to 0.9s.

---

### 2. Use Simple, Efficient Selectors

Browsers match selectors right-to-left. Keep them simple:

```css
/* ✅ Fast - single class */
.button {
  color: blue;
}

/* ❌ Slow - complex nesting */
.header .nav ul li a.active {
  color: blue;
}
```

Avoid descendant selectors and universal selectors. Use classes directly.

---

### 3. Animate Only Transform and Opacity

These properties are GPU-accelerated and don't trigger layout recalculation:

```css
/* ✅ Smooth 60fps animation */
.box {
  transition:
    transform 0.3s,
    opacity 0.3s;
}
.box:hover {
  transform: translateY(-10px);
  opacity: 0.8;
}

/* ❌ Janky animation - triggers layout */
.box:hover {
  top: -10px; /* Recalculates layout */
  height: 200px; /* Recalculates layout */
}
```

---

### 4. Use CSS Containment

Tell the browser which elements are independent to optimize rendering:

```css
.card {
  contain: layout style paint;
  /* Browser won't recalculate outside this element */
}
```

This prevents one card's changes from triggering recalculation of other cards.

---

### 5. Critical CSS Inline

Inline above-the-fold CSS in HTML to eliminate render-blocking:

```html
<head>
  <style>
    /* Critical CSS for above-fold content */
    .hero {
      background: blue;
      height: 100vh;
    }
  </style>
  <link
    rel="stylesheet"
    href="styles.css"
    media="print"
    onload="this.media='all'"
  />
</head>
```

The page renders immediately with inline styles while full CSS loads asynchronously.

---

### 6. Use will-change Sparingly

Hint to the browser about upcoming animations:

```css
.animated-element {
  will-change: transform;
}

.animated-element:hover {
  transform: scale(1.1);
}
```

**Warning:** Don't overuse. Too many `will-change` declarations consume memory.

---

## Measured Impact

On a production marketing website:

**Before optimization:**

- CSS file size: 850KB
- First Contentful Paint: 3.2s
- Animation FPS: 35fps

**After optimization:**

- CSS file size: 45KB (95% reduction)
- First Contentful Paint: 0.9s
- Animation FPS: 60fps

---

## Key Takeaways

CSS blocks rendering and inefficient styles delay page display. Split CSS by route, use simple selectors, and remove unused styles.

Animate only transform and opacity for GPU-accelerated 60fps performance. Use CSS containment to isolate rendering updates.

Inline critical CSS for above-the-fold content to eliminate render-blocking. These optimizations reduce CSS size by 90% and improve paint times by 70%.

# <div>React Hooks:</div> When and How to Use

On my first React project with hooks, I used useState for everything even data that never changed. I had 15 useState declarations in one component when I only needed 3. Understanding which hook solves which problem transformed how I write React components.

---

## <div>The Problem:</div> Using the Wrong Hook or Too Many Hooks

Developers often misuse hooks useState when useMemo is needed, useEffect when useCallback suffices, or creating new hooks when built-in ones exist. This leads to unnecessary re-renders, complex code, and performance issues.

```javascript
// ❌ Wrong - Recalculates on every render
function ProductList({ products }) {
  const expensive = products.filter((p) => p.price > 100);
  return <div>{expensive.length} expensive items</div>;
}
```

**The consequence:** Components re-render unnecessarily, calculations run repeatedly, and app performance suffers.

---

## Why This Needs to Be Solved

Misusing hooks creates performance problems, complex code, and bugs. Understanding each hook's purpose helps you write efficient, maintainable React components.

---

## The Built-In Hooks:

### useState - Component State

Use when you need to track values that change and trigger re-renders.

```jsx
function Counter() {
  const [count, setCount] = useState(0);
  return <button onClick={() => setCount(count + 1)}>{count}</button>;
}
```

**When to use:** User input, toggles, counters, form fields.

---

### useEffect - Side Effects

Use for operations outside React's rendering API calls, subscriptions, DOM manipulation.

```javascript
function UserProfile({ userId }) {
  const [user, setUser] = useState(null);

  useEffect(() => {
    fetch(`/api/users/${userId}`)
      .then((res) => res.json())
      .then(setUser);
  }, [userId]); // Runs when userId changes

  return <div>{user?.name}</div>;
}
```

**When to use:** Data fetching, subscriptions, timers, DOM updates.

---

### useContext - Share Data Globally

Use to avoid prop drilling for global data like theme, user, or settings.

```javascript
const ThemeContext = createContext();

function App() {
  return (
    <ThemeContext.Provider value="dark">
      <Toolbar />
    </ThemeContext.Provider>
  );
}

function Toolbar() {
  const theme = useContext(ThemeContext);
  return <div className={theme}>Toolbar</div>;
}
```

**When to use:** Theme, authentication, language settings.

---

### useMemo - Memoize Expensive Calculations

Use to cache calculation results and avoid recalculating on every render.

```javascript
function ProductList({ products }) {
  const expensive = useMemo(
    () => products.filter((p) => p.price > 100),
    [products],
  );

  return <div>{expensive.length} expensive items</div>;
}
```

**When to use:** Expensive filtering, sorting, or calculations.

---

### useCallback - Memoize Functions

Use to prevent recreating functions on every render, especially for child component props.

```javascript
function Parent() {
  const [count, setCount] = useState(0);

  const handleClick = useCallback(() => {
    console.log("Clicked");
  }, []); // Function doesn't change

  return <Child onClick={handleClick} />;
}
```

**When to use:** Passing callbacks to optimized child components.

---

### useRef - Persist Values Without Re-renders

Use for values that persist across renders but don't trigger updates DOM references, timers, previous values.

```javascript
function Timer() {
  const intervalRef = useRef();

  const start = () => {
    intervalRef.current = setInterval(() => {
      console.log("Tick");
    }, 1000);
  };

  const stop = () => {
    clearInterval(intervalRef.current);
  };

  return (
    <div>
      <button onClick={start}>Start</button>
      <button onClick={stop}>Stop</button>
    </div>
  );
}
```

**When to use:** DOM elements, interval/timeout IDs, previous values.

---

### useReducer - Complex State Logic

Use when state updates depend on previous state or involve multiple sub-values.

```javascript
function reducer(state, action) {
  switch (action.type) {
    case "increment":
      return { count: state.count + 1 };
    case "decrement":
      return { count: state.count - 1 };
    default:
      return state;
  }
}

function Counter() {
  const [state, dispatch] = useReducer(reducer, { count: 0 });

  return (
    <div>
      {state.count}
      <button onClick={() => dispatch({ type: "increment" })}>+</button>
    </div>
  );
}
```

**When to use:** Complex state logic, multiple related state values.

---

## Quick Decision Guide

**Need to track changing values?** → useState  
**Need to run code after render?** → useEffect  
**Expensive calculation?** → useMemo  
**Passing functions to children?** → useCallback  
**Reference DOM elements?** → useRef  
**Complex state logic?** → useReducer  
**Share data globally?** → useContext

---

## Common Mistakes

**Mistake #1:** Using useEffect for calculations. Use useMemo instead.

**Mistake #2:** Wrapping every function in useCallback. Only optimize when needed.

**Mistake #3:** Missing dependencies in useEffect/useMemo/useCallback arrays.

**Mistake #4:** Using useState for values that don't trigger re-renders. Use useRef.

---

## Key Takeaways

Each React hook solves a specific problem. Using the right hook creates cleaner, more performant components.

useState for changing values, useEffect for side effects, useMemo for expensive calculations, useCallback for function memoization, useRef for persistent non-reactive values.

Understanding when to use each hook prevents unnecessary re-renders and keeps components simple and maintainable.

# React Custom Hooks: <div>Improving</div> Reusability

On one project, I had five different components all implementing the same data fetching logic useEffect with loading states, error handling, and cleanup. When I needed to add retry logic, I had to update it in five places. That's when I learned custom hooks aren't just a nice-to-have; they're essential for maintainable React applications.

---

## <div>The Problem:</div> Duplicated Logic Across Components

React components often need the same functionality fetching data, managing forms, handling window resize, or detecting clicks outside an element. Without custom hooks, this logic gets copy-pasted across multiple components.

```javascript
// Repeated in 5 different components
function UserProfile() {
  const [data, setData] = useState(null);
  const [loading, setLoading] = useState(true);
  const [error, setError] = useState(null);

  useEffect(() => {
    fetch("/api/user")
      .then((res) => res.json())
      .then((data) => {
        setData(data);
        setLoading(false);
      })
      .catch((err) => {
        setError(err);
        setLoading(false);
      });
  }, []);

  if (loading) return <div>Loading...</div>;
  if (error) return <div>Error: {error.message}</div>;
  return <div>{data.name}</div>;
}
```

**The consequence:** When requirements change (add caching, retry logic, or timeout handling), you update the same code in multiple places. This leads to bugs, inconsistency, and wasted time.

---

## Why This Needs to Be Solved

Code duplication creates three critical problems:

**Maintenance nightmare:** Fixing bugs or adding features requires updating multiple files. You inevitably miss some, creating inconsistent behavior.

**Testing complexity:** The same logic tested in multiple components wastes effort and increases test suite size.

**Component bloat:** Components become large and hard to understand when they mix business logic with shared utilities.

---

## <div>The Solution:</div> Custom Hooks

Custom hooks extract reusable logic into functions that can be shared across components. They follow React's rules of hooks and can use other hooks internally.

### Creating a Fetch Hook

Extract the repeated fetch logic into a custom hook:

```javascript
function useFetch(url) {
  const [data, setData] = useState(null);
  const [loading, setLoading] = useState(true);
  const [error, setError] = useState(null);

  useEffect(() => {
    setLoading(true);
    fetch(url)
      .then((res) => res.json())
      .then((data) => {
        setData(data);
        setLoading(false);
      })
      .catch((err) => {
        setError(err);
        setLoading(false);
      });
  }, [url]);

  return { data, loading, error };
}

// Now components are simple
function UserProfile() {
  const { data, loading, error } = useFetch("/api/user");

  if (loading) return <div>Loading...</div>;
  if (error) return <div>Error: {error.message}</div>;
  return <div>{data.name}</div>;
}
```

**The benefit:** Fetch logic exists in one place. Updates apply everywhere automatically. Components focus on rendering, not data fetching mechanics.

---

### Form Handling Hook

Another common pattern form input management:

```javascript
function useForm(initialValues) {
  const [values, setValues] = useState(initialValues);

  const handleChange = (e) => {
    setValues({
      ...values,
      [e.target.name]: e.target.value,
    });
  };

  const reset = () => setValues(initialValues);

  return { values, handleChange, reset };
}

// Usage
function LoginForm() {
  const { values, handleChange, reset } = useForm({
    email: "",
    password: "",
  });

  const handleSubmit = (e) => {
    e.preventDefault();
    // Submit values
    reset();
  };

  return (
    <form onSubmit={handleSubmit}>
      <input
        name="email"
        value={values.email}
        onChange={handleChange}
      />
      <input
        name="password"
        value={values.password}
        onChange={handleChange}
      />
      <button type="submit">Login</button>
    </form>
  );
}
```

---

### Local Storage Hook

Sync state with localStorage automatically:

```javascript
function useLocalStorage(key, initialValue) {
  const [value, setValue] = useState(() => {
    const stored = localStorage.getItem(key);
    return stored ? JSON.parse(stored) : initialValue;
  });

  useEffect(() => {
    localStorage.setItem(key, JSON.stringify(value));
  }, [key, value]);

  return [value, setValue];
}

// Usage
function Settings() {
  const [theme, setTheme] = useLocalStorage("theme", "light");

  return (
    <button onClick={() => setTheme(theme === "light" ? "dark" : "light")}>
      Toggle Theme
    </button>
  );
}
```

---

## Key Principles

**Start with "use":** Custom hooks must start with "use" so React can enforce rules of hooks.

**Return what's needed:** Return objects for multiple values, arrays for ordered pairs like useState.

**Keep hooks focused:** Each hook should do one thing well. Don't create giant multi-purpose hooks.

**Compose hooks together:** Build complex hooks from simpler ones.

---

## Measured Impact

After extracting custom hooks on a production project:

**Before:**

- Average component size: 180 lines
- Code duplication: 35%
- Bug fix time: 45 minutes (updating multiple files)

**After:**

- Average component size: 80 lines
- Code duplication: 8%
- Bug fix time: 10 minutes (single hook update)

---

## Key Takeaways

Custom hooks eliminate code duplication by extracting reusable logic into shareable functions. This reduces component complexity, improves maintainability, and makes testing easier.

Extract common patterns like data fetching, form handling, and side effects into focused custom hooks. Components become cleaner and more focused on rendering logic.

# <div>Code Reviews:</div> Catching Bugs Before Production

Early in my career, we merged code without proper reviews. A simple typo in a conditional check caused a payment form to fail for Safari users. We didn't catch it for three days during which we lost dozens of transactions. That's when I learned code reviews aren't optional; they're essential.

Leading a team of 5 developers, I've seen how proper code reviews catch bugs, share knowledge, and maintain code quality. Without structured reviews, technical debt accumulates and production issues multiply.

---

## <div>The Problem:</div> Code Goes to Production Without Proper Review

Many teams skip code reviews or treat them as a formality. Developers merge their own pull requests, or reviewers approve without actually reading the code.

Here's what typically happens without proper reviews:

```javascript
// Merged without review
export default function CheckoutForm() {
  const [total, setTotal] = useState(0);

  const calculateTotal = () => {
    const subtotal = items.reduce((sum, item) => sum + item.price, 0);
    const tax = subtotal * 0.08;
    setTotal(subtotal + tax); // Bug: Not rounding to 2 decimals
  };

  return <div>Total: ${total}</div>; // Shows $23.456789 instead of $23.46
}
```

**What goes wrong:**

**Logic bugs slip through:** The calculation works but displays incorrect formatting. Users see confusing prices.

**Performance issues unnoticed:** Expensive operations run on every render without optimization. The app feels slow.

**Security vulnerabilities:** User input isn't validated. XSS attacks become possible.

**Inconsistent patterns:** Each developer implements features differently. Codebase becomes unmaintainable.

On one project, lack of reviews led to three separate pagination implementations across different pages, making future maintenance painful.

---

## Why This Needs to Be Solved

Skipping code reviews creates four critical problems:

**Production bugs:** Issues that could be caught in 5 minutes of review become production incidents requiring hours to debug and fix.

**Technical debt accumulation:** Poor code patterns spread across the codebase. What could be fixed during review becomes a major refactoring project.

**Knowledge silos:** Only the original author understands their code. When they leave or switch projects, nobody can maintain it.

**Missed learning opportunities:** Junior developers don't get feedback. Senior developers don't share their expertise.

On a recent project, implementing structured code reviews reduced production bugs by 65% in the first month.

---

## <div>The Solution:</div> Structured Code Review Process

Effective code reviews follow a consistent checklist and focus on what matters most. Here's my approach:

### 1. Review for Correctness First

Before anything else, verify the code actually works as intended:

**Does it solve the stated problem?** Test the feature locally or review screenshots/videos.

**Are edge cases handled?** Check for null values, empty arrays, error states.

```javascript
// ❌ Needs review feedback
function UserProfile({ user }) {
  return <h1>{user.name}</h1>; // What if user is null?
}

// ✅ After review feedback
function UserProfile({ user }) {
  if (!user) return <div>Loading...</div>;
  return <h1>{user.name}</h1>;
}
```

### 2. Check Performance Implications

Look for common performance mistakes:

**Unnecessary re-renders:** Missing dependencies in useEffect, inline function definitions in props.

**Expensive operations in render:** Heavy calculations or array operations without useMemo.

```javascript
// ❌ Flag in review
function ProductList({ products }) {
  return products
    .filter((p) => p.active)
    .map((p) => (
      <ProductCard
        key={p.id}
        product={p}
      />
    )); // Filters on every render
}

// ✅ Suggest improvement
function ProductList({ products }) {
  const activeProducts = useMemo(
    () => products.filter((p) => p.active),
    [products],
  );

  return activeProducts.map((p) => (
    <ProductCard
      key={p.id}
      product={p}
    />
  ));
}
```

### 3. Verify Security and Data Handling

Frontend security is often overlooked in reviews:

**User input validation:** Check for sanitization before rendering or sending to API.

**Sensitive data exposure:** Ensure API keys and secrets aren't in client code.

**XSS vulnerabilities:** Verify dangerouslySetInnerHTML is used safely.

```javascript
// ❌ Security issue - flag in review
function Comment({ text }) {
  return <div dangerouslySetInnerHTML={{ __html: text }} />;
}

// ✅ Safe approach
function Comment({ text }) {
  return <div>{text}</div>; // React escapes by default
}
```

### 4. Review Code Organization

Check if the code follows project patterns:

**Component structure:** Is logic in the right place? Should this be a custom hook?

**File organization:** Are files in correct directories?

**Naming conventions:** Do variable and function names clearly convey purpose?

```javascript
// ❌ Suggest refactoring
function ProductPage() {
  const [data, setData] = useState(null);

  useEffect(() => {
    fetch("/api/products")
      .then((r) => r.json())
      .then(setData);
  }, []);

  // 200 lines of component logic...
}

// ✅ Better organization
function ProductPage() {
  const { products, isLoading } = useProducts(); // Custom hook

  if (isLoading) return <Loading />;
  return <ProductList products={products} />;
}
```

### 5. Suggest Improvements, Don't Demand Perfection

Code reviews should be constructive, not blocking:

**Critical issues:** Must fix before merge (bugs, security, breaking changes)

**Suggestions:** Nice to have but not blockers (refactoring, alternative approaches)

**Nitpicks:** Style preferences that can be handled by linters

```
❌ Bad review comment:
"This is wrong. Do it like this instead."

✅ Good review comment:
"Consider using useMemo here to avoid recalculating on every render.
The current approach works but might cause performance issues with
large datasets. What do you think?"
```

---

## My Code Review Checklist

I use this quick checklist on every review:

**Functionality:**

- Does it work as described?
- Are edge cases handled?
- Is error handling present?

**Performance:**

- Any unnecessary re-renders?
- Expensive operations optimized?
- Images/assets properly optimized?

**Code Quality:**

- Follows project patterns?
- Clear naming and structure?
- Properly typed (if using TypeScript)?

**Security:**

- User input validated?
- No sensitive data exposed?
- Safe rendering of dynamic content?

**Testing:**

- Are there tests (if required)?
- Do tests cover edge cases?

This checklist takes 5-10 minutes per pull request but catches 80% of common issues.

---

## Common Review Mistakes

**Mistake #1: Reviewing too much code at once.** Pull requests over 400 lines are hard to review properly. I ask developers to split large features into smaller PRs.

**Mistake #2: Focusing only on style.** Linters handle formatting. Reviews should focus on logic, architecture, and correctness.

**Mistake #3: Not testing locally.** Reading code isn't enough. I checkout the branch and test critical features.

**Mistake #4: Being too harsh or too lenient.** Balance is key catch real issues but don't block progress over personal preferences.

---

## Measured Impact

On a production team implementing structured reviews:

**Before structured reviews:**

- Production bugs per month: 12-15
- Average fix time: 4 hours
- Code quality score: 6.2/10

**After structured reviews:**

- Production bugs per month: 4-5 (67% reduction)
- Average fix time: 1.5 hours
- Code quality score: 8.5/10

**Additional benefits:**

- Onboarding time reduced by 40%
- Knowledge sharing improved across team
- Technical debt decreased measurably

---

## Key Takeaways

Code reviews are essential for catching bugs before production, maintaining code quality, and sharing knowledge across teams. Without proper reviews, technical debt accumulates and production issues multiply.

Focus reviews on correctness, performance, security, and code organization. Use a consistent checklist to ensure nothing is missed.

Balance thoroughness with speed aim for 5-10 minute reviews that catch critical issues without blocking progress. Provide constructive feedback, not demands.

Structured code reviews reduce production bugs by 60-70% while improving team knowledge and code maintainability.

# <div>GSAP ScrollTrigger</div> in React

On one of my early projects, I added beautiful GSAP scroll animations that looked amazing in development. Two weeks after launch, users reported the page getting progressively slower. The culprit? I wasn't properly cleaning up GSAP instances in React components, causing memory leaks with every route change.

React's component lifecycle doesn't naturally align with GSAP's animation instances. This mismatch creates specific problems that need solving for production-ready scroll animations.

---

## <div>The Problem:</div> React's Lifecycle vs GSAP Instances

React components mount and unmount frequently especially in single-page applications with routing. GSAP creates animation instances and ScrollTrigger observers that persist beyond component unmounting if not properly cleaned up.

Here's what happens with naive GSAP implementation:

```javascript
import { useEffect } from "react";
import gsap from "gsap";
import { ScrollTrigger } from "gsap/ScrollTrigger";

gsap.registerPlugin(ScrollTrigger);

export default function Hero() {
  useEffect(() => {
    gsap.to(".hero-title", {
      scrollTrigger: {
        trigger: ".hero-section",
        start: "top center",
        end: "bottom center",
        scrub: true,
      },
      opacity: 0,
      y: -100,
    });
  }, []);

  return (
    <div className="hero-section">
      <h1 className="hero-title">Welcome</h1>
    </div>
  );
}
```

**What goes wrong:**

**Memory leaks:** ScrollTrigger instances aren't destroyed when the component unmounts. Navigate away and back, and you create duplicate observers.

**Performance degradation:** Multiple ScrollTrigger instances fire simultaneously on the same scroll events, causing stuttering and increased CPU usage.

**Stale references:** GSAP holds references to DOM elements that no longer exist after unmounting, causing console errors and unexpected behavior.

On a recent project, this resulted in scroll performance dropping from 60fps to 30fps after just 3-4 route changes.

---

## Why This Needs to Be Solved

Unmanaged GSAP animations create three critical production issues:

**User experience degradation:** Animations that start smooth become janky over time as memory usage increases. Users on lower-end devices notice this immediately.

**Resource waste:** Each unmounted component leaves behind active scroll listeners and animation timelines consuming memory and CPU cycles.

**Unpredictable behavior:** Stale GSAP instances can trigger animations on elements that don't exist anymore, causing console errors and broken interactions.

On a marketing website with 10+ animated sections, improper cleanup led to 50+ active ScrollTrigger instances after normal browsing. The page became unusable.

---

## <div>The Solution:</div> Proper GSAP Lifecycle Management

The key is matching GSAP's lifecycle to React's component lifecycle. Create animations when components mount, and critically, destroy them when components unmount.

### Implementation with useEffect Cleanup

Here's the correct way to implement GSAP in React:

```javascript
import { useEffect, useRef } from "react";
import gsap from "gsap";
import { ScrollTrigger } from "gsap/ScrollTrigger";

gsap.registerPlugin(ScrollTrigger);

export default function Hero() {
  const heroRef = useRef(null);
  const titleRef = useRef(null);

  useEffect(() => {
    const ctx = gsap.context(() => {
      gsap.to(titleRef.current, {
        scrollTrigger: {
          trigger: heroRef.current,
          start: "top center",
          end: "bottom center",
          scrub: true,
        },
        opacity: 0,
        y: -100,
      });
    }, heroRef);

    return () => ctx.revert(); // Cleanup on unmount
  }, []);

  return (
    <div
      ref={heroRef}
      className="hero-section"
    >
      <h1 ref={titleRef}>Welcome</h1>
    </div>
  );
}
```

**How this solves the problem:**

**gsap.context()** scopes all animations to a specific component. When the component unmounts, calling `ctx.revert()` automatically kills all animations and ScrollTriggers created within that context.

**useRef for DOM references** ensures we're always animating the correct elements, not relying on class selectors that might match multiple elements across components.

**Cleanup function** in useEffect guarantees that GSAP instances are destroyed when React unmounts the component.

**Result:** No memory leaks, no performance degradation, no stale references.

---

### Using the Official useGSAP Hook

GSAP provides an official React hook that handles cleanup automatically. This is now my preferred approach:

```javascript
import { useRef } from "react";
import gsap from "gsap";
import { useGSAP } from "@gsap/react";
import { ScrollTrigger } from "gsap/ScrollTrigger";

gsap.registerPlugin(ScrollTrigger);

export default function Hero() {
  const heroRef = useRef(null);

  useGSAP(
    () => {
      gsap.to(".hero-title", {
        scrollTrigger: {
          trigger: heroRef.current,
          start: "top center",
          end: "bottom center",
          scrub: true,
        },
        opacity: 0,
        y: -100,
      });
    },
    { scope: heroRef },
  ); // Automatically handles cleanup

  return (
    <div
      ref={heroRef}
      className="hero-section"
    >
      <h1 className="hero-title">Welcome</h1>
    </div>
  );
}
```

**Why useGSAP is better:**

The hook automatically reverts all animations on unmount without manual cleanup code. The `scope` option limits selectors to the component, preventing conflicts with other components using the same class names.

---

## Complex Animation Sequences

For more sophisticated scroll animations, I use GSAP timelines with proper scoping:

```javascript
export default function Features() {
  const containerRef = useRef(null);

  useGSAP(
    () => {
      const tl = gsap.timeline({
        scrollTrigger: {
          trigger: containerRef.current,
          start: "top 80%",
          end: "bottom 20%",
          scrub: 1,
        },
      });

      tl.from(".feature-1", { opacity: 0, y: 50 })
        .from(".feature-2", { opacity: 0, y: 50 }, "-=0.3")
        .from(".feature-3", { opacity: 0, y: 50 }, "-=0.3");
    },
    { scope: containerRef },
  );

  return (
    <div ref={containerRef}>
      <div className="feature-1">Feature 1</div>
      <div className="feature-2">Feature 2</div>
      <div className="feature-3">Feature 3</div>
    </div>
  );
}
```

The entire timeline and all its ScrollTriggers are automatically cleaned up when the component unmounts.

---

## Performance Optimization Techniques

Beyond proper cleanup, these techniques ensure smooth 60fps animations:

### Use `will-change` CSS Property

Tell the browser which properties will animate so it can optimize rendering:

```javascript
useGSAP(
  () => {
    gsap.set(".animated-element", { willChange: "transform, opacity" });

    gsap.to(".animated-element", {
      scrollTrigger: {
        trigger: ".section",
        scrub: true,
      },
      y: -200,
      opacity: 0,
    });
  },
  { scope: containerRef },
);
```

### Animate Transform and Opacity Only

These properties are GPU-accelerated and don't trigger layout recalculations:

```javascript
// ✅ Good: GPU-accelerated
gsap.to(element, { x: 100, y: 50, scale: 1.2, opacity: 0.5 });

// ❌ Bad: Triggers layout recalculation
gsap.to(element, { width: 500, height: 300, top: 100 });
```

### Debounce Resize Events

When ScrollTrigger needs to recalculate on window resize:

```javascript
useEffect(() => {
  const handleResize = () => {
    ScrollTrigger.refresh();
  };

  window.addEventListener("resize", handleResize);
  return () => window.removeEventListener("resize", handleResize);
}, []);
```

---

## Common Implementation Mistakes

**Mistake #1: Using class selectors without scoping.** Multiple components with `.hero-title` will all animate together. Always use refs or scope with gsap.context.

**Mistake #2: Forgetting to register plugins.** ScrollTrigger must be registered before use:

```javascript
import { ScrollTrigger } from "gsap/ScrollTrigger";
gsap.registerPlugin(ScrollTrigger); // Required!
```

**Mistake #3: Not refreshing ScrollTrigger after dynamic content loads.** When content height changes, ScrollTrigger positions become incorrect:

```javascript
useEffect(() => {
  if (dataLoaded) {
    ScrollTrigger.refresh(); // Recalculate positions
  }
}, [dataLoaded]);
```

**Mistake #4: Animating during SSR.** GSAP requires the DOM, which doesn't exist during server-side rendering in Next.js. Always check for window:

```javascript
useEffect(() => {
  if (typeof window !== "undefined") {
    // GSAP animations here
  }
}, []);
```

---

## Measured Impact

On a marketing website with scroll animations:

**Before proper cleanup:**

- Memory usage after 5 route changes: 180MB
- Scroll performance: 35fps
- Active ScrollTrigger instances: 47

**After implementing useGSAP:**

- Memory usage after 5 route changes: 62MB
- Scroll performance: 60fps
- Active ScrollTrigger instances: 9 (only current page)

These optimizations contributed to a 25% increase in landing page conversions by improving perceived performance.

---

## Key Takeaways

React's component lifecycle and GSAP's persistent animations don't align naturally. Without proper cleanup, scroll animations cause memory leaks and performance degradation in production.

Use `gsap.context()` or the official `useGSAP` hook to automatically clean up animations when components unmount. Always scope animations to component refs to prevent cross-component conflicts.

Optimize performance by animating only transform and opacity properties, using `will-change` CSS, and refreshing ScrollTrigger when dynamic content loads.

Properly implemented GSAP scroll animations enhance user experience without sacrificing performance, creating engaging interfaces that users love.

# <div>Advanced TypeScript </div> Patterns for React Component Libraries

Ever built a Button that works great until someone needs it to be a Link? Or a Table that breaks when data shape changes? Here are TypeScript patterns that make components flexible and foolproof.

---

## Pattern 1: Polymorphic Components with `as`

The `as` prop lets components render as any element:

```typescript
interface BoxProps<T extends React.ElementType> {
  as?: T;
  children: React.ReactNode;
}

const Box = <T extends React.ElementType = 'div'>({
  as: Component = 'div',
  children,
  ...props
}: BoxProps<T> & React.ComponentPropsWithoutRef<T>) => {
  return <Component {...props}>{children}</Component>;
};

// Usage
<Box as="a" href="/home">Link</Box>
<Box as="button" onClick={handleClick}>Button</Box>
```

TypeScript suggests correct props based on the `as` value.

---

## Pattern 2: Omit for Prop Conflicts

Remove conflicting native props:

```typescript
interface ButtonProps extends Omit<React.ButtonHTMLAttributes<HTMLButtonElement>, 'size'> {
  size?: 'sm' | 'md' | 'lg';
  variant?: 'primary' | 'secondary';
}

const Button = ({ size = 'md', variant = 'primary', ...props }: ButtonProps) => (
  <button className={`btn-${size} btn-${variant}`} {...props} />
);
```

Native `size` attribute is removed, replaced with our design system size.

---

## Pattern 3: Discriminated Unions for Variants

Prevent invalid prop combinations:

```typescript
type NotificationProps =
  | { variant: 'success' | 'error'; message: string; }
  | { variant: 'custom'; message: string; icon: React.ReactNode; color: string; };

const Notification = (props: NotificationProps) => {
  switch(props.variant) {
    case 'success': return <div className="bg-green-100">{props.message}</div>;
    case 'custom': return <div style={{backgroundColor: props.color}}>{props.icon}</div>;
  }
};
```

TypeScript ensures required props exist for each variant.

---

## Pattern 4: Generic Data Components

Components that work with any data type:

```typescript
interface TableProps<T> {
  data: T[];
  columns: { key: keyof T; header: string; }[];
}

function Table<T>({ data, columns }: TableProps<T>) {
  return (
    <table>
      {data.map((item, i) => (
        <tr key={i}>
          {columns.map(col => <td>{String(item[col.key])}</td>)}
        </tr>
      ))}
    </table>
  );
}

// TypeScript infers User type
<Table data={users} columns={[{ key: 'name', header: 'Name' }]} />
```

---

## Pattern 5: Conditional Props with Generics

Props that change based on another prop:

```typescript
interface ToggleProps<T = false> {
  multi?: T;
  onChange: T extends true ? (items: string[]) => void : (checked: boolean) => void;
}

<Toggle onChange={(val) => console.log(val)} /> // val is boolean
<Toggle multi onChange={(val) => console.log(val)} /> // val is string[]
```

---

## Key Takeaways

- **Polymorphic components** eliminate wrapper components
- **Omit** prevents native prop conflicts
- **Discriminated unions** enforce correct prop combinations
- **Generics** make components reusable across data types

Your component library becomes self-documenting and impossible to misuse.

# <div>Debouncing in React: </div> Solving Excessive Re-renders and API Calls

Have you ever experienced, that a search input that is making 23 API requests for a single search, a request per keystroke. In such scenario, backend team will not be so happy, and user will also experience lag with every character. This is a common React behavior that requires attention.

---

## <div>The Problem:</div> React's Frequent Updates

React re-renders components whenever state changes. When you build a search input, every keystroke updates state, triggering a re-render and any side effects tied to that state.

Here's what happens without debouncing:

```javascript
export default function SearchBar() {
  const [query, setQuery] = useState("");

  const handleSearch = async (searchTerm) => {
    const response = await fetch(`/api/search?q=${searchTerm}`);
    const data = await response.json();
    setResults(data);
  };

  return
    <input
      onChange={(e) => {
        setQuery(e.target.value);
        handleSearch(e.target.value); // Fires on EVERY keystroke!
      }}
    />
  );
}
```

**User types "react"** → 5 keystrokes → 5 state updates → 5 re-renders → 5 API calls

This is React working exactly as designed, but it creates performance problems when tied to expensive operations like API calls, database writes, or complex calculations.

---

## Why This Needs to Be Solved

Excessive function execution causes three critical issues:

**Performance degradation:** Too many API calls slow down your application and create network congestion. Users experience lag and unresponsiveness.

**Wasted resources:** Your backend processes and responds to requests that get immediately replaced by new ones. This increases server costs and infrastructure load.

**Poor user experience:** Users don't need results while they're still typing. They want results when they've finished forming their search term.

On a recent project, search without debouncing averaged 8-12 API calls per query. Most were wasted because users were still typing.

---

## <div>The Solution:</div> Debouncing

Debouncing delays function execution until the user stops performing an action for a specified time. Instead of running on every keystroke, it waits until typing pauses.

**Concept:** Wait 500ms after the last keystroke before making the API call. If another keystroke happens within 500ms, reset the timer.

### Implementation with useEffect

Here's how I implement debouncing in React:

```javascript
export default function SearchBar() {
  const [query, setQuery] = useState("");
  const [debouncedQuery, setDebouncedQuery] = useState("");

  // Debounce logic
  useEffect(() => {
    const timer = setTimeout(() => {
      setDebouncedQuery(query);
    }, 500);

    return () => clearTimeout(timer); // Cancel previous timer
  }, [query]);

  // API call only when debounced value changes
  useEffect(() => {
    if (debouncedQuery) {
      fetch(`/api/search?q=${debouncedQuery}`)
        .then((res) => res.json())
        .then((data) => setResults(data));
    }
  }, [debouncedQuery]);

  return (
    <input
      value={query}
      onChange={(e) => setQuery(e.target.value)}
    />
  );
}
```

**How it works:**

1. User types → `query` state updates immediately (UI stays responsive)
2. Timer starts for 500ms
3. If user types again within 500ms → timer resets
4. After 500ms of no typing → `debouncedQuery` updates
5. API call fires only once

**Result:** Typing "react" = 1 API call instead of 5

---

### Reusable Custom Hook

Creating a reusable hook makes debouncing cleaner across your application:

```javascript
function useDebounce(value, delay = 500) {
  const [debouncedValue, setDebouncedValue] = useState(value);

  useEffect(() => {
    const timer = setTimeout(() => setDebouncedValue(value), delay);
    return () => clearTimeout(timer);
  }, [value, delay]);

  return debouncedValue;
}

// Usage
export default function SearchBar() {
  const [query, setQuery] = useState("");
  const debouncedQuery = useDebounce(query, 500);

  useEffect(() => {
    if (debouncedQuery) {
      // Make API call
    }
  }, [debouncedQuery]);

  return <input onChange={(e) => setQuery(e.target.value)} />;
}
```

---

## Common Use Cases

**Search/Autocomplete:** Wait for user to finish typing before fetching results

**Form Auto-save:** Save to database after user stops editing, not on every keystroke

**Input Validation:** Validate after user completes input, reducing unnecessary checks

**Resize Handlers:** Recalculate layout after window resize stops, not during

---

## Key Implementation Points

**Choose appropriate delay times:**

- Search inputs: 300-500ms
- Auto-save: 1000-2000ms
- Resize handlers: 200-300ms

**Always clean up timers** in the useEffect cleanup function to prevent memory leaks

**Check for meaningful values** before executing expensive operations:

```javascript
useEffect(() => {
  if (debouncedQuery.trim()) {
    // Only search non-empty strings
    handleSearch(debouncedQuery);
  }
}, [debouncedQuery]);
```

---

## Measured Impact

On a production e-commerce project:

**Before:** 8-12 API calls per search  
**After:** 1-2 API calls per search  
**Reduction:** 85% fewer requests

Users didn't notice the 500ms delay, but our backend infrastructure certainly noticed the reduced load.

---

## Key Takeaways

React's frequent state updates cause excessive function execution when tied to expensive operations like API calls. Debouncing solves this by delaying execution until activity stops, dramatically reducing unnecessary operations.

Implement debouncing with `useEffect` and timers, or create a reusable `useDebounce` hook for cleaner code. Choose delay times based on your specific use case and always clean up timers properly.

The result is better performance, reduced server costs, and improved user experience all from a simple optimization technique.

---

