# Error <div> Boundaries </div> and Fallbacks

One JavaScript error in a component. The whole UI disappears. White screen. User confused. You lost a customer.

This is React's default behavior and it's terrible for user experience.

---

## <div>The Problem:</div> Brittle Components

```typescript
// One error here 💥
const UserProfile = ({ userId }) => {
  const user = fetchUser(userId); // Throws if userId invalid
  return <div>{user.name}</div>; // Entire app crashes
};

// App dies. User sees nothing.
```

React unmounts everything. No recovery. No helpful message. Just... nothing.

---

## <div>The Solution:</div> Error Boundaries

Error boundaries catch JavaScript errors anywhere in their child tree:

```typescript
import { Component, ErrorInfo, ReactNode } from 'react';

interface Props {
  children: ReactNode;
  fallback?: ReactNode;
}

interface State {
  hasError: boolean;
  error?: Error;
}

class ErrorBoundary extends Component<Props, State> {
  constructor(props: Props) {
    super(props);
    this.state = { hasError: false };
  }

  static getDerivedStateFromError(error: Error): State {
    return { hasError: true, error };
  }

  componentDidCatch(error: Error, errorInfo: ErrorInfo) {
    // Log to error reporting service
    console.error('Caught error:', error, errorInfo);
  }

  render() {
    if (this.state.hasError) {
      return this.props.fallback || (
        <div className="p-4 bg-red-50 border border-red-200 rounded">
          <h2>Something went wrong</h2>
          <p className="text-red-600">{this.state.error?.message}</p>
          <button
            onClick={() => this.setState({ hasError: false })}
            className="mt-2 px-4 py-2 bg-red-600 text-white rounded"
          >
            Try again
          </button>
        </div>
      );
    }

    return this.props.children;
  }
}
```

---

## Usage: Wrap Risky Components

```typescript
function App() {
  return (
    <div>
      <Header />

      {/* This component might fail independently */}
      <ErrorBoundary fallback={<UserProfileError />}>
        <UserProfile userId={userId} />
      </ErrorBoundary>

      {/* Rest of app still works */}
      <Footer />
    </div>
  );
}

// Custom fallback
const UserProfileError = () => (
  <div className="text-center p-8">
    <p>Couldn't load profile. Please refresh.</p>
    <button onClick={() => window.location.reload()}>
      Refresh
    </button>
  </div>
);
```

---

## Granular Boundaries

Don't wrap everything in one boundary. Be strategic:

```typescript
function Dashboard() {
  return (
    <div>
      <h1>Dashboard</h1>

      <ErrorBoundary fallback={<WidgetError name="Sales" />}>
        <SalesWidget />
      </ErrorBoundary>

      <ErrorBoundary fallback={<WidgetError name="Analytics" />}>
        <AnalyticsWidget />
      </ErrorBoundary>

      <ErrorBoundary fallback={<WidgetError name="Recent Activity" />}>
        <ActivityFeed />
      </ErrorBoundary>
    </div>
  );
}
```

One widget fails? The rest still work. Users keep using your app.

---

## With React Router

```typescript
import { useRouteError } from 'react-router-dom';

// Route error element
function RouteErrorBoundary() {
  const error = useRouteError();

  return (
    <div className="p-8 text-center">
      <h1 className="text-2xl font-bold mb-4">Oops!</h1>
      <p className="mb-4">Sorry, something went wrong.</p>
      <pre className="bg-gray-100 p-4 rounded">
        {error?.message || 'Unknown error'}
      </pre>
      <button
        onClick={() => window.location.href = '/'}
        className="mt-4 px-4 py-2 bg-blue-600 text-white rounded"
      >
        Go Home
      </button>
    </div>
  );
}

// In router config
const router = createBrowserRouter([
  {
    path: '/',
    element: <Root />,
    errorElement: <RouteErrorBoundary />,
    children: [...]
  }
]);
```

---

## Error Recovery Patterns

**1. Retry mechanism**

```typescript
class RetryErrorBoundary extends Component {
  state = { hasError: false, error: null };

  handleRetry = () => {
    this.setState({ hasError: false, error: null });
  };

  render() {
    if (this.state.hasError) {
      return (
        <div>
          <p>Error: {this.state.error?.message}</p>
          <button onClick={this.handleRetry}>Retry</button>
        </div>
      );
    }
    return this.props.children;
  }
}
```

**2. Fallback with context**

```typescript
const ErrorFallback = ({ error, resetErrorBoundary }) => (
  <div role="alert">
    <p>Something went wrong:</p>
    <pre>{error.message}</pre>
    <button onClick={resetErrorBoundary}>Try again</button>
  </div>
);
```

---

## Integration with Error Tracking

```typescript
class SentryErrorBoundary extends Component {
  componentDidCatch(error: Error, errorInfo: ErrorInfo) {
    // Send to Sentry, LogRocket, etc.
    Sentry.captureException(error, { extra: errorInfo });
  }

  render() {
    return this.props.children;
  }
}
```

---

## What Error Boundaries DON'T Catch

- Event handlers (use try/catch instead)
- Asynchronous code (setTimeout, promises)
- Server-side rendering
- Errors thrown in the boundary itself

For async code:

```typescript
const handleClick = async () => {
  try {
    await riskyOperation();
  } catch (error) {
    // Handle or show error UI
  }
};
```

---

## Key Takeaways

1. **Wrap risky components individually** isolate failures
2. **Provide helpful fallbacks** don't just show "Error"
3. **Log errors** you can't fix what you don't know about
4. **Offer recovery options** retry, refresh, go back

Your app will fail. That's inevitable. What matters is how gracefully it fails.

---

# File Uploads in React: Complete Guide

File uploads seem simple until you need to show progress, handle errors, or support drag-and-drop. Then things get complicated.

Here's how to build robust file uploads in React from basic to advanced.

---

## Basic Single File Upload

The simplest approach uses a form with `multipart/form-data`:

```typescript
import { useState, FormEvent } from 'react';

export const SimpleUpload = () => {
  const [file, setFile] = useState<File | null>(null);
  const [uploading, setUploading] = useState(false);

  const handleSubmit = async (e: FormEvent) => {
    e.preventDefault();
    if (!file) return;

    const formData = new FormData();
    formData.append('file', file);

    setUploading(true);
    try {
      const response = await fetch('/api/upload', {
        method: 'POST',
        body: formData
      });

      if (response.ok) {
        alert('Upload successful!');
        setFile(null);
      }
    } catch (error) {
      console.error('Upload failed:', error);
    } finally {
      setUploading(false);
    }
  };

  return (
    <form onSubmit={handleSubmit}>
      <input
        type="file"
        onChange={(e) => setFile(e.target.files?.[0] || null)}
        accept="image/*"
      />
      <button type="submit" disabled={!file || uploading}>
        {uploading ? 'Uploading...' : 'Upload'}
      </button>
    </form>
  );
};
```

The `accept` attribute restricts file types. `FormData` handles binary data correctly.

---

## File Validation

Never trust the client alone, but validate early for better UX:

```typescript
const validateFile = (file: File): string | null => {
  const maxSize = 5 * 1024 * 1024; // 5MB
  const allowedTypes = ["image/jpeg", "image/png", "image/gif"];

  if (!allowedTypes.includes(file.type)) {
    return "Only JPG, PNG, and GIF images are allowed";
  }

  if (file.size > maxSize) {
    return "File size must be less than 5MB";
  }

  return null;
};

// In your component
const handleFileChange = (e: React.ChangeEvent<HTMLInputElement>) => {
  const selected = e.target.files?.[0];
  if (!selected) return;

  const error = validateFile(selected);
  if (error) {
    setError(error);
    setFile(null);
  } else {
    setError(null);
    setFile(selected);
  }
};
```

Show validation errors immediately, not after upload attempt.

---

## Upload Progress with Axios

Fetch API doesn't track progress. Axios does:

```bash
npm install axios
```

```typescript
import axios from 'axios';
import { useState } from 'react';

export const ProgressUpload = () => {
  const [progress, setProgress] = useState(0);

  const handleUpload = async (file: File) => {
    const formData = new FormData();
    formData.append('file', file);

    try {
      const response = await axios.post('/api/upload', formData, {
        onUploadProgress: (progressEvent) => {
          if (progressEvent.total) {
            const percent = Math.round(
              (progressEvent.loaded * 100) / progressEvent.total
            );
            setProgress(percent);
          }
        }
      });

      console.log('Upload complete:', response.data);
    } catch (error) {
      console.error('Upload failed:', error);
    }
  };

  return (
    <div>
      <input
        type="file"
        onChange={(e) => {
          const file = e.target.files?.[0];
          if (file) handleUpload(file);
        }}
      />
      {progress > 0 && (
        <div className="w-full bg-gray-200 rounded">
          <div
            className="bg-blue-600 text-xs text-white p-1 rounded"
            style={{ width: `${progress}%` }}
          >
            {progress}%
          </div>
        </div>
      )}
    </div>
  );
};
```

Users appreciate seeing that something is happening.

---

## Multi-File Upload

Allow selecting multiple files at once:

```typescript
import { useState } from 'react';

export const MultiFileUpload = () => {
  const [files, setFiles] = useState<File[]>([]);

  const handleFileChange = (e: React.ChangeEvent<HTMLInputElement>) => {
    if (e.target.files) {
      setFiles(Array.from(e.target.files));
    }
  };

  const handleUpload = async () => {
    const formData = new FormData();
    files.forEach(file => {
      formData.append('files', file);
    });

    try {
      await fetch('/api/upload-multiple', {
        method: 'POST',
        body: formData
      });
      alert('All files uploaded!');
      setFiles([]);
    } catch (error) {
      console.error('Upload failed:', error);
    }
  };

  return (
    <div>
      <input
        type="file"
        multiple
        onChange={handleFileChange}
      />

      {files.length > 0 && (
        <div>
          <h4>Selected files:</h4>
          <ul>
            {files.map(file => (
              <li key={file.name}>
                {file.name} ({(file.size / 1024).toFixed(2)} KB)
              </li>
            ))}
          </ul>
          <button onClick={handleUpload}>
            Upload {files.length} files
          </button>
        </div>
      )}
    </div>
  );
};
```

The `multiple` attribute lets users select several files at once.

---

## Image Previews

Show users what they're about to upload:

```typescript
import { useState, useEffect } from 'react';

export const ImagePreview = () => {
  const [file, setFile] = useState<File | null>(null);
  const [preview, setPreview] = useState<string | null>(null);

  useEffect(() => {
    if (!file) {
      setPreview(null);
      return;
    }

    const objectUrl = URL.createObjectURL(file);
    setPreview(objectUrl);

    // Clean up to avoid memory leaks
    return () => URL.revokeObjectURL(objectUrl);
  }, [file]);

  return (
    <div>
      <input
        type="file"
        accept="image/*"
        onChange={(e) => setFile(e.target.files?.[0] || null)}
      />

      {preview && (
        <div className="mt-4">
          <img
            src={preview}
            alt="Preview"
            className="max-w-xs max-h-48 object-contain border rounded"
          />
          <button
            onClick={() => setFile(null)}
            className="mt-2 text-red-500 text-sm"
          >
            Remove
          </button>
        </div>
      )}
    </div>
  );
};
```

`URL.createObjectURL()` creates a temporary URL you can use in an img tag. Always revoke it when done.

---

## Drag and Drop Upload

The modern way users expect to drag files:

```typescript
import { useState, DragEvent } from 'react';

export const DragDropUpload = () => {
  const [isDragging, setIsDragging] = useState(false);

  const handleDragEnter = (e: DragEvent) => {
    e.preventDefault();
    e.stopPropagation();
    setIsDragging(true);
  };

  const handleDragLeave = (e: DragEvent) => {
    e.preventDefault();
    e.stopPropagation();
    setIsDragging(false);
  };

  const handleDragOver = (e: DragEvent) => {
    e.preventDefault();
    e.stopPropagation();
  };

  const handleDrop = (e: DragEvent) => {
    e.preventDefault();
    e.stopPropagation();
    setIsDragging(false);

    const files = Array.from(e.dataTransfer.files);
    if (files.length > 0) {
      // Handle the files
      console.log('Dropped files:', files);
    }
  };

  return (
    <div
      onDragEnter={handleDragEnter}
      onDragLeave={handleDragLeave}
      onDragOver={handleDragOver}
      onDrop={handleDrop}
      className={`border-2 border-dashed rounded-lg p-8 text-center transition ${
        isDragging
          ? 'border-blue-500 bg-blue-50'
          : 'border-gray-300'
      }`}
    >
      <div className="text-4xl mb-2">📁</div>
      <p className="text-gray-600">
        Drag and drop files here, or{' '}
        <label className="text-blue-500 cursor-pointer hover:underline">
          browse
          <input
            type="file"
            className="hidden"
            onChange={(e) => {
              const files = e.target.files;
              if (files) console.log('Selected:', files);
            }}
          />
        </label>
      </p>
      <p className="text-sm text-gray-400 mt-2">
        Supported: Images, PDFs, Documents
      </p>
    </div>
  );
};
```

Visual feedback during drag makes the interaction feel responsive.

---

## Complete Custom Hook

Combine everything into a reusable hook:

```typescript
import { useState, useCallback } from "react";
import axios from "axios";

interface UseFileUploadOptions {
  url: string;
  multiple?: boolean;
  maxSize?: number;
  allowedTypes?: string[];
  onSuccess?: (response: any) => void;
  onError?: (error: Error) => void;
}

export function useFileUpload({
  url,
  multiple = false,
  maxSize = 5 * 1024 * 1024,
  allowedTypes = [],
  onSuccess,
  onError,
}: UseFileUploadOptions) {
  const [files, setFiles] = useState<File[]>([]);
  const [progress, setProgress] = useState<number[]>([]);
  const [uploading, setUploading] = useState(false);

  const validateFile = useCallback(
    (file: File): string | null => {
      if (allowedTypes.length > 0 && !allowedTypes.includes(file.type)) {
        return "File type not allowed";
      }
      if (file.size > maxSize) {
        return "File exceeds size limit";
      }
      return null;
    },
    [allowedTypes, maxSize],
  );

  const addFiles = useCallback(
    (newFiles: File[]) => {
      const validFiles = newFiles.filter((file) => !validateFile(file));
      setFiles((prev) => (multiple ? [...prev, ...validFiles] : validFiles));
      setProgress((prev) => [...prev, ...Array(validFiles.length).fill(0)]);
    },
    [multiple, validateFile],
  );

  const upload = useCallback(async () => {
    if (files.length === 0) return;

    setUploading(true);
    const formData = new FormData();
    files.forEach((file) => formData.append("files", file));

    try {
      const response = await axios.post(url, formData, {
        onUploadProgress: (progressEvent) => {
          if (progressEvent.total) {
            const percent = (progressEvent.loaded * 100) / progressEvent.total;
            setProgress(Array(files.length).fill(percent));
          }
        },
      });

      onSuccess?.(response.data);
      setFiles([]);
      setProgress([]);
    } catch (error) {
      onError?.(error as Error);
    } finally {
      setUploading(false);
    }
  }, [files, url, onSuccess, onError]);

  const removeFile = useCallback((index: number) => {
    setFiles((prev) => prev.filter((_, i) => i !== index));
    setProgress((prev) => prev.filter((_, i) => i !== index));
  }, []);

  return {
    files,
    progress,
    uploading,
    addFiles,
    upload,
    removeFile,
    validateFile,
  };
}
```

Usage:

```typescript
const { files, progress, uploading, addFiles, upload } = useFileUpload({
  url: "/api/upload",
  multiple: true,
  allowedTypes: ["image/jpeg", "image/png"],
});
```

---

## Key Takeaways

1. **Validate files early** size, type, and count before upload
2. **Show progress** users want to know upload is working
3. **Provide previews** especially for images
4. **Support drag-and-drop** modern users expect it
5. **Clean up object URLs** avoid memory leaks
6. **Handle multiple files** with progress per file

File uploads don't have to be painful. With these patterns, you'll give users a smooth experience every time.

# Form Validation in React: Zod + React Hook Form

Forms are everywhere. So are bugs from unexpected data strings where numbers should be, missing required fields, emails without @ symbols.

Here's how to build forms that validate at runtime while keeping TypeScript perfect.

---

## <div>The Problem:</div> TypeScript Disappears at Runtime

TypeScript is great, but it's compile-time only. That user input from a form? TypeScript trusts it's a string. But what if it's null? Undefined? An object?

```typescript
// TypeScript thinks this is safe
const handleSubmit = (data: { email: string; age: number }) => {
  // But what if age is actually "twenty" at runtime? 💥
};
```

---

## <div>The Solution:</div> Zod for Runtime Validation

Zod creates schemas that validate at runtime AND infer TypeScript types:

```typescript
import { z } from 'zod';

// Define schema once
const userSchema = z.object({
  email: z.string().email('Invalid email format'),
  age: z.number().min(18, 'Must be 18 or older'),
  name: z.string().min(2, 'Name too short'),
  role: z.enum(['user', 'admin']).default('user')
});

// TypeScript type automatically inferred
type UserFormData = z.infer<typeof userSchema>;
// Equivalent to: { email: string; age: number; name: string; role: 'user' | 'admin' }
```

One source of truth. Zero duplication.

---

## React Hook Form + Zod = ❤️

React Hook Form integrates seamlessly with Zod:

```typescript
import { useForm } from 'react-hook-form';
import { zodResolver } from '@hookform/resolvers/zod';

const userSchema = z.object({
  email: z.string().email('Check your email format'),
  password: z.string().min(8, 'Password must be at least 8 characters'),
  confirmPassword: z.string()
}).refine(data => data.password === data.confirmPassword, {
  message: "Passwords don't match",
  path: ['confirmPassword']
});

type FormData = z.infer<typeof userSchema>;

export const RegisterForm = () => {
  const { register, handleSubmit, formState: { errors } } = useForm<FormData>({
    resolver: zodResolver(userSchema)
  });

  const onSubmit = (data: FormData) => {
    // data is FULLY typed and validated
    console.log(data); // { email: string; password: string; confirmPassword: string }
  };

  return (
    <form onSubmit={handleSubmit(onSubmit)}>
      <input {...register('email')} />
      {errors.email && <span>{errors.email.message}</span>}
      
      <input type="password" {...register('password')} />
      {errors.password && <span>{errors.password.message}</span>}
      
      <input type="password" {...register('confirmPassword')} />
      {errors.confirmPassword && <span>{errors.confirmPassword.message}</span>}
      
      <button type="submit">Register</button>
    </form>
  );
};
```

---

## Advanced Patterns

### Complex Validation

```typescript
const productSchema = z.object({
  name: z.string().min(3),
  price: z.number().positive(),
  tags: z.array(z.string()).min(1, 'At least one tag required'),
  metadata: z.record(z.string()).optional(),
  inStock: z.boolean(),
  releaseDate: z.date().min(new Date(), 'Must be future date')
});
```

### Conditional Fields

```typescript
const schema = z.discriminatedUnion('type', [
  z.object({ type: z.literal('text'), maxLength: z.number() }),
  z.object({ type: z.literal('number'), min: z.number(), max: z.number() })
]);
```

### API Integration

```typescript
const handleSubmit = async (data: FormData) => {
  try {
    const response = await fetch('/api/users', {
      method: 'POST',
      body: JSON.stringify(data) // ✅ Type-safe
    });
  } catch (error) {
    // Handle error
  }
};
```

---

## Why This Pattern Wins

| Without Zod + RHF | With Zod + RHF |
|-------------------|----------------|
| Manual validation logic | Declarative schemas |
| Type safety at compile only | Runtime + compile safety |
| Duplicate types | Single source of truth |
| Error-prone parsing | Automatic parsing |

---

## Key Takeaways

1. **Define schemas once** get types and validation together
2. **Zod refines** handle cross-field validation (like password matching)
3. **React Hook Form resolver** connects everything automatically
4. **Data is safe** by the time it reaches onSubmit

Your backend will thank you. Your users will thank you. And you'll sleep better knowing "twenty" will never reach your age field.

# Styling React Components: CSS Approaches Compared

Styling in React isn't one-size-fits-all. Global CSS causes conflicts. Inline styles lack features. CSS-in-JS adds runtime overhead.

Let's compare the most popular approaches so you can choose what fits your project.

---

## The Core Challenge

In traditional HTML/CSS, styles are global. That's fine for small sites but dangerous in component-based architectures.

```css
/* This button style affects EVERY button */
button {
  background: blue;
  color: white;
}
```

In React, you want styles scoped to components. Different solutions solve this differently.

---

## Approach 1: CSS Modules

CSS Modules keep CSS in separate files but automatically generate unique class names to prevent collisions.

**Setup:** Name your files with `.module.css` extension.

```css
/* Button.module.css */
.btn {
  padding: 10px 16px;
  border: none;
  border-radius: 4px;
  cursor: pointer;
}

.primary {
  background-color: #007bff;
  color: white;
}

.secondary {
  background-color: #6c757d;
  color: white;
}
```

```typescript
// Button.tsx
import styles from './Button.module.css';

interface ButtonProps {
  variant: 'primary' | 'secondary';
  children: React.ReactNode;
}

export const Button = ({ variant, children }: ButtonProps) => {
  return (
    <button className={`${styles.btn} ${styles[variant]}`}>
      {children}
    </button>
  );
};
```

**How it works:** When built, `.btn` becomes something like `Button_btn__2Je3C`. No conflicts, ever .

**Pros:**

- Regular CSS syntax no learning curve
- Scoped by default no leakage
- Works with preprocessors like Sass

**Cons:**

- One extra file per component
- Conditional classes require template literals or helper libraries

**Best for:** Teams comfortable with traditional CSS who want scoping without paradigm shifts.

---

## Approach 2: Tailwind CSS

Tailwind takes a utility-first approach. Instead of writing custom CSS, you compose styles using predefined classes directly in JSX .

**Setup:**

```bash
npm install -D tailwindcss postcss autoprefixer
npx tailwindcss init
```

Configure `tailwind.config.js`:

```javascript
module.exports = {
  content: ["./src/**/*.{js,jsx,ts,tsx}"],
  theme: { extend: {} },
  plugins: [],
};
```

Add directives to `index.css`:

```css
@tailwind base;
@tailwind components;
@tailwind utilities;
```

**Usage:**

```typescript
export const ProductCard = ({ product }) => {
  return (
    <div className="bg-white rounded-lg shadow-md overflow-hidden hover:shadow-lg transition">
      <img src={product.image} alt={product.name} className="w-full h-48 object-cover" />
      <div className="p-4">
        <h3 className="text-lg font-semibold text-gray-800">{product.name}</h3>
        <p className="text-gray-600 mt-1">${product.price}</p>
        <button className="mt-3 w-full bg-blue-600 hover:bg-blue-700 text-white py-2 rounded">
          Add to Cart
        </button>
      </div>
    </div>
  );
};
```

**Pros:**

- Rapid development no context switching
- Consistent design system out of the box
- Small production CSS (unused styles are purged)
- Responsive design with simple prefixes like `md:text-lg`

**Cons:**

- Verbose className strings can be hard to read
- Learning curve for class names
- Custom designs require configuration changes

**Best for:** Teams building fast, design-consistent applications, especially with design systems.

---

## Approach 3: Styled-Components (CSS-in-JS)

Styled-components let you write actual CSS in your JavaScript files using tagged template literals .

**Setup:**

```bash
npm install styled-components
npm install --save-dev @types/styled-components
```

**Usage:**

```typescript
import styled from 'styled-components';

interface ButtonProps {
  primary?: boolean;
}

const Button = styled.button<ButtonProps>`
  background-color: ${props => props.primary ? '#007bff' : '#6c757d'};
  color: white;
  padding: 10px 16px;
  border: none;
  border-radius: 4px;
  font-size: 16px;
  cursor: pointer;

  &:hover {
    background-color: ${props => props.primary ? '#0056b3' : '#5a6268'};
  }
`;

export const App = () => (
  <div>
    <Button primary>Primary</Button>
    <Button>Secondary</Button>
  </div>
);
```

Each styled component is a React component with attached styles. Props can dynamically change styles .

**Pros:**

- Styles are truly scoped to components
- Dynamic styling based on props is natural
- No class name collisions
- Can use all CSS features (pseudo-classes, media queries)

**Cons:**

- Adds runtime JavaScript increases bundle size
- Performance impact on rendering
- Slower initial paint

**Best for:** Applications needing highly dynamic, prop-driven styles, or teams who prefer colocating everything in JavaScript.

---

## Approach 4: Shadcn/ui + Tailwind

This isn't a styling method per se, but a popular combination: Tailwind CSS with pre-built, accessible components from shadcn/ui .

```typescript
import { Button } from "@/components/ui/button";
import { Card } from "@/components/ui/card";

export const ProfileCard = () => (
  <Card className="p-6">
    <h2 className="text-xl font-bold">Profile</h2>
    <p className="text-gray-600 mt-2">User details here</p>
    <Button className="mt-4">Edit Profile</Button>
  </Card>
);
```

**Why it works:** You get component abstraction without losing Tailwind's flexibility. Components are yours to own and modify.

---

## Comparison Table

| Method            | Learning Curve | Bundle Size | Scoped? | Dynamic Styling | Best For                       |
| ----------------- | -------------- | ----------- | ------- | --------------- | ------------------------------ |
| CSS Modules       | Low            | Small       | Yes     | Limited         | Medium-large apps, CSS purists |
| Tailwind          | Medium         | Very small  | N/A     | Via className   | Rapid dev, design systems      |
| Styled-components | Medium         | Larger      | Yes     | Excellent       | Dynamic, prop-driven UIs       |
| Traditional CSS   | Lowest         | Small       | No      | No              | Small projects, prototypes     |

---

## Performance Considerations

**CSS Modules** and **Tailwind** generate static CSS files that browsers parse efficiently. They add zero runtime overhead .

**Styled-components** injects styles at runtime. For large apps with many dynamic styles, this can impact performance. However, for most apps, the difference is negligible .

Tailwind's purging removes unused CSS critical for production. A typical Tailwind build is often smaller than handwritten CSS .

---

## Key Takeaways

1. **No single best approach** it depends on your team and project
2. **CSS Modules** are great if you love regular CSS but want scoping
3. **Tailwind** is unbeatable for development speed and consistency
4. **Styled-components** shine when styles depend heavily on props
5. **Don't mix approaches** pick one and stay consistent

# Building Apps with React and Supabase

Setting up a backend is usually the slowest part of development. Databases, authentication, APIs it takes weeks.

Supabase changes that. It's an open-source Firebase alternative that gives you a Postgres database, authentication, and real-time subscriptions out of the box. Here's how to use it with React.

---

## Setting Up Supabase

First, create a project in the Supabase dashboard. Once it's ready, you'll get your project URL and anon key .

Install the client library:

```bash
npm install @supabase/supabase-js
```

Create a client instance in your app:

```typescript
// src/lib/supabase.ts
import { createClient } from '@supabase/supabase-js';

const supabaseUrl = import.meta.env.VITE_SUPABASE_URL;
const supabaseKey = import.meta.env.VITE_SUPABASE_ANON_KEY;

export const supabase = createClient(supabaseUrl, supabaseKey);
```

Add your credentials to `.env.local` :

```
VITE_SUPABASE_URL=https://your-project.supabase.co
VITE_SUPABASE_ANON_KEY=your-anon-key
```

---

## Database Queries

Supabase queries feel like writing SQL, but in JavaScript:

```typescript
// Fetch all records
const { data: users, error } = await supabase
  .from('users')
  .select('*');

// Fetch with filters
const { data: posts } = await supabase
  .from('posts')
  .select('id, title, author_id')
  .eq('published', true)
  .order('created_at', { ascending: false });

// Get single record
const { data: user } = await supabase
  .from('users')
  .select('*')
  .eq('id', userId)
  .single();

// Insert data
const { data: newPost } = await supabase
  .from('posts')
  .insert([{ title: 'Hello', content: 'World' }])
  .select();
```

The response always follows the same pattern: `data` contains your results, `error` contains any error that occurred .

---

## Authentication with Supabase

Supabase Auth handles email/password, magic links, and OAuth providers .

Here's a login component:

```typescript
import { useState } from 'react';
import { supabase } from '../lib/supabase';

export const LoginForm = () => {
  const [email, setEmail] = useState('');
  const [password, setPassword] = useState('');
  const [loading, setLoading] = useState(false);

  const handleLogin = async (e: React.FormEvent) => {
    e.preventDefault();
    setLoading(true);

    const { error } = await supabase.auth.signInWithPassword({
      email,
      password
    });

    if (error) {
      alert(error.message);
    }
    setLoading(false);
  };

  return (
    <form onSubmit={handleLogin}>
      <input
        type="email"
        value={email}
        onChange={(e) => setEmail(e.target.value)}
        placeholder="Email"
        required
      />
      <input
        type="password"
        value={password}
        onChange={(e) => setPassword(e.target.value)}
        placeholder="Password"
        required
      />
      <button type="submit" disabled={loading}>
        {loading ? 'Loading...' : 'Login'}
      </button>
    </form>
  );
};
```

For sign-up, use `supabase.auth.signUp()` with the same parameters .

---

## Managing Auth State

Supabase provides methods to track authentication state :

```typescript
import { useEffect, useState } from 'react';
import { supabase } from '../lib/supabase';
import type { User } from '@supabase/supabase-js';

export const useUser = () => {
  const [user, setUser] = useState<User | null>(null);
  const [loading, setLoading] = useState(true);

  useEffect(() => {
    // Get initial session
    supabase.auth.getSession().then(({ data: { session } }) => {
      setUser(session?.user ?? null);
      setLoading(false);
    });

    // Listen for auth changes
    const { data: { subscription } } = supabase.auth.onAuthStateChange(
      (_event, session) => {
        setUser(session?.user ?? null);
      }
    );

    return () => subscription.unsubscribe();
  }, []);

  return { user, loading };
};
```

Wrap your app with this context to provide user data everywhere .

---

## Protected Routes

Combine the auth state with React Router:

```typescript
import { Navigate, Outlet } from 'react-router-dom';
import { useUser } from '../hooks/useUser';

export const ProtectedRoute = () => {
  const { user, loading } = useUser();

  if (loading) {
    return <div>Loading...</div>;
  }

  return user ? <Outlet /> : <Navigate to="/login" replace />;
};
```

Usage in your router:

```typescript
<Route element={<ProtectedRoute />}>
  <Route path="/dashboard" element={<Dashboard />} />
  <Route path="/profile" element={<Profile />} />
</Route>
```

---

## Real-Time Subscriptions

One of Supabase's best features is real-time updates :

```typescript
import { useEffect, useState } from 'react';
import { supabase } from '../lib/supabase';

export const LiveMessages = () => {
  const [messages, setMessages] = useState([]);

  useEffect(() => {
    // Fetch initial messages
    const fetchMessages = async () => {
      const { data } = await supabase
        .from('messages')
        .select('*')
        .order('created_at', { ascending: false });
      
      setMessages(data || []);
    };

    fetchMessages();

    // Subscribe to new messages
    const subscription = supabase
      .channel('public:messages')
      .on('postgres_changes', 
        { event: 'INSERT', schema: 'public', table: 'messages' },
        (payload) => {
          setMessages(prev => [payload.new, ...prev]);
        }
      )
      .subscribe();

    return () => {
      subscription.unsubscribe();
    };
  }, []);

  return (
    <div>
      {messages.map(msg => (
        <div key={msg.id}>{msg.content}</div>
      ))}
    </div>
  );
};
```

The subscription listens for INSERT events and updates the UI instantly .

---

## Row Level Security

Supabase uses Postgres Row Level Security (RLS) to control data access . Enable it in the dashboard and create policies:

```sql
-- Allow users to read only their own profile
CREATE POLICY "Users can view own profile"
ON profiles FOR SELECT
USING (auth.uid() = id);

-- Allow users to update only their own profile
CREATE POLICY "Users can update own profile"
ON profiles FOR UPDATE
USING (auth.uid() = id);
```

RLS ensures that even if someone gets your anon key, they can't access data they shouldn't .

---

## Key Takeaways

1. **Supabase replaces multiple backends** database, auth, and real-time in one
2. **Queries are intuitive** chain methods like `.select()`, `.eq()`, `.order()`
3. **Auth state is easy to manage** `getSession()` and `onAuthStateChange`
4. **Real-time subscriptions** keep UI in sync automatically
5. **RLS is essential** always enable it and create proper policies

With Supabase, you can build full-stack features in hours instead of weeks.

# React Suspense and Lazy Loading: Code Splitting Made Easy

Your bundle keeps growing. 500KB. 1MB. 2MB. Users on slow networks wait longer. Some leave.

The fix? Don't load everything at once.

---

## <div>The Problem:</div> One Giant Bundle

```typescript
// Without lazy loading - everything loads upfront
import Dashboard from "./pages/Dashboard";
import Settings from "./pages/Settings";
import AdminPanel from "./pages/AdminPanel";
import Analytics from "./pages/Analytics";

// User just wants to login, but downloads 2MB of admin features
```

Users pay for code they never use.

---

## <div>The Solution:</div> React.lazy() + Suspense

```typescript
import { lazy, Suspense } from 'react';
import { BrowserRouter, Routes, Route } from 'react-router-dom';

// These become separate chunks
const Dashboard = lazy(() => import('./pages/Dashboard'));
const Settings = lazy(() => import('./pages/Settings'));
const AdminPanel = lazy(() => import('./pages/AdminPanel'));
const Analytics = lazy(() => import('./pages/Analytics'));

// Loading fallback
const PageLoader = () => (
  <div className="flex items-center justify-center h-screen">
    <div className="animate-spin rounded-full h-12 w-12 border-b-2 border-blue-600" />
  </div>
);

function App() {
  return (
    <BrowserRouter>
      <Suspense fallback={<PageLoader />}>
        <Routes>
          <Route path="/" element={<Dashboard />} />
          <Route path="/settings" element={<Settings />} />
          <Route path="/admin" element={<AdminPanel />} />
          <Route path="/analytics" element={<Analytics />} />
        </Routes>
      </Suspense>
    </BrowserRouter>
  );
}
```

**Result:** Dashboard loads fast. Admin panel loads only when user visits `/admin`.

---

## Route-Based Code Splitting

This is the sweet spot split by routes:

```typescript
// routes.ts
const routes = [
  {
    path: '/',
    component: lazy(() => import('./pages/Home')),
    exact: true
  },
  {
    path: '/products/:id',
    component: lazy(() => import('./pages/ProductDetail')),
  },
  {
    path: '/checkout',
    component: lazy(() => import('./pages/Checkout')),
  },
  {
    path: '/dashboard',
    component: lazy(() => import('./pages/Dashboard')),
    protected: true,
    roles: ['admin', 'user']
  }
];

// Generate routes dynamically
export const AppRoutes = () => (
  <Routes>
    {routes.map((route) => (
      <Route
        key={route.path}
        path={route.path}
        element={
          <Suspense fallback={<PageLoader />}>
            {route.protected ? (
              <ProtectedRoute roles={route.roles}>
                <route.component />
              </ProtectedRoute>
            ) : (
              <route.component />
            )}
          </Suspense>
        }
      />
    ))}
  </Routes>
);
```

---

## Component-Level Lazy Loading

Sometimes routes aren't enough lazy load heavy components:

```typescript
import { lazy, Suspense, useState } from 'react';

// Heavy chart library - load only when needed
const SalesChart = lazy(() => import('./charts/SalesChart'));
const UserMap = lazy(() => import('./maps/UserMap'));

const Dashboard = () => {
  const [showCharts, setShowCharts] = useState(false);

  return (
    <div>
      <button onClick={() => setShowCharts(true)}>
        Load Analytics
      </button>

      {showCharts && (
        <Suspense fallback={<ChartSkeleton />}>
          <SalesChart />
          <UserMap />
        </Suspense>
      )}
    </div>
  );
};

// Skeleton loader
const ChartSkeleton = () => (
  <div className="grid gap-4">
    <div className="h-64 bg-gray-200 animate-pulse rounded" />
    <div className="h-64 bg-gray-200 animate-pulse rounded" />
  </div>
);
```

---

## Named Exports with React.lazy()

React.lazy() works with default exports. For named exports:

```typescript
// charts/SalesChart.tsx
export const SalesChart = () => { ... };
export const SalesChartSkeleton = () => { ... };

// Lazy load named export
const SalesChart = lazy(() =>
  import('./charts/SalesChart').then(module => ({
    default: module.SalesChart
  }))
);
```

---

## Preloading for Better UX

Anticipate user navigation:

```typescript
const ProductPage = lazy(() => import('./pages/Product'));

// Preload when user hovers over link
const ProductLink = ({ productId }) => {
  const preloadProduct = () => {
    const ProductPage = import('./pages/Product');
  };

  return (
    <Link
      to={`/product/${productId}`}
      onMouseEnter={preloadProduct}
      onFocus={preloadProduct}
    >
      View Product
    </Link>
  );
};
```

---

## Error Handling with Boundaries

Combine lazy loading with error boundaries:

```typescript
import { lazy, Suspense } from 'react';
import { ErrorBoundary } from 'react-error-boundary';

const ProductPage = lazy(() => import('./pages/Product'));

const ProductRoute = () => (
  <ErrorBoundary
    fallback={<ProductError />}
    onError={logError}
  >
    <Suspense fallback={<ProductSkeleton />}>
      <ProductPage />
    </Suspense>
  </ErrorBoundary>
);
```

---

## Measuring Impact

| Metric              | Before | After              |
| ------------------- | ------ | ------------------ |
| Initial bundle      | 2.4 MB | 412 KB             |
| Load time (3G)      | 8.2s   | 2.1s               |
| Time to interactive | 9.5s   | 2.8s               |
| Pages loaded        | All    | Only what's needed |

---

## Best Practices

1. **Split at route boundaries** it's natural and predictable
2. **Use meaningful skeletons** don't just show a spinner
3. **Preload critical routes** like the next most likely page
4. **Set reasonable chunk names** for debugging

```typescript
// Named chunks for easier debugging
const AdminPanel = lazy(
  () => import(/* webpackChunkName: "admin" */ "./pages/AdminPanel"),
);
```

---

## Key Takeaways

1. **Lazy load by route** biggest impact, least effort
2. **Add Suspense fallbacks** never show nothing
3. **Preload intelligently** hover, viewport, idle time
4. **Measure bundle sizes** know what you're shipping

Your users don't need your entire app at once. Give them just enough to start, then load the rest while they read.

# Authentication Flows with TypeScript

Authentication is the gatekeeper of your app. Get it wrong, and user data leaks. Get it right, and users barely notice it's there.

Let's build bulletproof authentication in React with TypeScript covering token storage, protected routes, refresh flows, and role-based access.

---

## The Token Storage Dilemma

Where should you store JWTs? This single decision impacts your entire security model.

**localStorage is convenient but vulnerable.** Any XSS attack can read `localStorage.getItem('token')` and steal user sessions. A single malicious script compromises every user.

**HTTP-only cookies are more secure.** The server sets a cookie that JavaScript cannot read. The browser sends it automatically with requests.

```typescript
// ❌ Vulnerable - XSS can steal this
localStorage.setItem("token", jwt);

// ✅ Secure - Server sets HTTP-only cookie
// Response header: Set-Cookie: token=...; HttpOnly; Secure; SameSite=Strict
```

The trade-off? You need a backend that supports cookies and CORS. For most production apps, it's worth the effort.

---

## Building the Auth Context

Authentication state needs to be accessible everywhere. React Context provides that global access with proper TypeScript typing.

Here's the core structure:

```typescript
interface User {
  id: string;
  email: string;
  name: string;
  roles: string[];
}

interface AuthContextType {
  user: User | null;
  isLoading: boolean;
  login: (email: string, password: string) => Promise<void>;
  logout: () => Promise<void>;
  hasRole: (role: string) => boolean;
}
```

The context provider checks session status on mount and exposes login/logout methods. A custom hook ensures the context is used correctly:

```typescript
export const useAuth = () => {
  const context = useContext(AuthContext);
  if (!context) {
    throw new Error("useAuth must be used within AuthProvider");
  }
  return context;
};
```

This pattern eliminates runtime errors from missing providers.

---

## Session Persistence

When a user refreshes the page, React state resets. You need to verify their session with the server.

```typescript
useEffect(() => {
  const checkSession = async () => {
    try {
      const response = await fetch("/api/auth/session", {
        credentials: "include", // Send cookies
      });

      if (response.ok) {
        const userData = await response.json();
        setUser(userData);
      }
    } finally {
      setIsLoading(false);
    }
  };

  checkSession();
}, []);
```

While this request runs, show a loading spinner. Never render protected UI before confirming authentication.

---

## Protecting Routes

Not every route should be accessible to unauthenticated users. A protected route wrapper solves this:

```typescript
const ProtectedRoute = ({ requiredRole }: { requiredRole?: string }) => {
  const { user, isLoading, hasRole } = useAuth();

  if (isLoading) return <LoadingSpinner />;
  if (!user) return <Navigate to="/login" replace />;
  if (requiredRole && !hasRole(requiredRole)) {
    return <Navigate to="/unauthorized" replace />;
  }

  return <Outlet />;
};
```

Use it in your router configuration:

```typescript
<Route element={<ProtectedRoute />}>
  <Route path="/dashboard" element={<Dashboard />} />
</Route>

<Route element={<ProtectedRoute requiredRole="admin" />}>
  <Route path="/admin" element={<AdminPanel />} />
</Route>
```

---

## Token Refresh Pattern

JWTs expire typically after 15-30 minutes. Users shouldn't have to log in again.

An axios interceptor handles this automatically:

```typescript
api.interceptors.response.use(
  (response) => response,
  async (error) => {
    const originalRequest = error.config;

    if (error.response?.status === 401 && !originalRequest._retry) {
      originalRequest._retry = true;

      try {
        await axios.post(
          "/api/auth/refresh",
          {},
          {
            withCredentials: true,
          },
        );
        return api(originalRequest);
      } catch (refreshError) {
        window.location.href = "/login";
        return Promise.reject(refreshError);
      }
    }

    return Promise.reject(error);
  },
);
```

The user never knows their token expired. The request fails, refreshes silently, and retries all in the background.

---

## Role-Based Access Control

Many apps need different permission levels. Two layers of protection work together:

**Route level protection** prevents unauthorized navigation:

```typescript
<Route element={<ProtectedRoute requiredRole="admin" />}>
  <Route path="/admin/users" element={<UserManagement />} />
</Route>
```

**Component level protection** shows or hides UI elements:

```typescript
const AdminOnly = ({ children }: { children: React.ReactNode }) => {
  const { hasRole } = useAuth();
  return hasRole('admin') ? <>{children}</> : null;
};

// Usage
<AdminOnly>
  <button onClick={deleteUser}>Delete User</button>
</AdminOnly>
```

Remember: component-level hiding is for UX, not security. Always validate permissions server-side.

---

## The Login Form

A well-built login form balances user experience with security:

```typescript
const LoginForm = () => {
  const { login } = useAuth();
  const [error, setError] = useState('');

  const onSubmit = async (data: { email: string; password: string }) => {
    try {
      setError('');
      await login(data.email, data.password);
      navigate('/dashboard');
    } catch {
      setError('Invalid email or password');
    }
  };

  return (
    <form onSubmit={handleSubmit(onSubmit)}>
      <input type="email" {...register('email')} />
      <input type="password" {...register('password')} />
      {error && <div className="error">{error}</div>}
      <button type="submit">Login</button>
    </form>
  );
};
```

**Key principles:**

- Validate email format immediately
- Use generic error messages to prevent user enumeration
- Disable submit button during submission
- Clear errors on new attempt

---

## Logout Best Practices

Logout must do two things: clear local state and invalidate the server session.

```typescript
const logout = async () => {
  await fetch("/api/auth/logout", {
    method: "POST",
    credentials: "include",
  });
  setUser(null);
  navigate("/login");
};
```

If you only clear local state, the session cookie remains valid. Anyone with access to that computer could still use the session.

---

## Security Checklist

- ✅ **HTTP-only cookies** for tokens (never localStorage)
- ✅ **Short-lived access tokens** with refresh rotation
- ✅ **Rate limiting** on login endpoints
- ✅ **CORS** configured to allow only your frontend domain
- ✅ **CSRF protection** for state-changing requests
- ✅ **Input validation** on both client and server
- ✅ **Session invalidation** on logout

---

## Key Takeaways

1. **HTTP-only cookies** are safer than localStorage for tokens
2. **Context + custom hooks** make auth accessible anywhere
3. **Protected routes** prevent unauthorized access at navigation level
4. **Token refresh** happens silently in the background
5. **Role-based checks** add fine-grained control

Authentication isn't just login forms it's building trust. Get it right, and users never think about it. Get it wrong, and they never come back.

# React TypeScript Best Practices: Writing Code That Scales

You know that feeling when you rename a prop and spend the next 30 minutes hunting down every component that breaks? Or when you pass a string to a component expecting a number and discover it only after your app crashes in production?

TypeScript solves these problems, but only if you use it right. After refactoring countless React codebases, I've learned that TypeScript is like a smart assistant it helps most when you set it up properly.

Here are the practices that actually make a difference.

---

## 1. Define Component Props Explicitly

The biggest mistake? Using `any` for props. You're basically telling TypeScript, "Don't help me here."

**Don't do this:**

```typescript
const Button = (props: any) => { ... }
```

**Do this:**

```typescript
interface ButtonProps {
  variant: 'primary' | 'secondary';
  size: 'sm' | 'md' | 'lg';
  children: React.ReactNode;
  onClick?: () => void;
  disabled?: boolean;
}

const Button = ({ variant, size, children, onClick, disabled }: ButtonProps) => { ... }
```

Now TypeScript catches mistakes instantly. Try passing `variant="danger"` TypeScript stops you cold.

---

## 2. Prefer Interfaces for Props, Types for Unions

There's an ongoing debate: interface or type? Here's my rule of thumb:

- Use **interface** for component props and objects that might extend
- Use **type** for unions, intersections, and complex mappings

```typescript
// Interface for props (can extend later)
interface CardProps {
  title: string;
  content: string;
}

// Type for unions
type Status = "idle" | "loading" | "success" | "error";

// Type for complex combinations
type ApiResponse = SuccessResponse | ErrorResponse;
```

Interfaces give better error messages in TypeScript and merge automatically when extended.

---

## 3. Handle Children Properly

`children` trips up everyone. The type `any` works but defeats the purpose. Use `ReactNode`:

```typescript
interface ContainerProps {
  children: React.ReactNode;  // Accepts anything React can render
  className?: string;
}

const Container = ({ children, className }: ContainerProps) => (
  <div className={className}>{children}</div>
);
```

This accepts strings, numbers, elements, arrays, fragments everything React supports.

---

## 4. Use Discriminated Unions for Complex State

When a component has multiple states, discriminated unions are a game-changer:

```typescript
type ComponentState =
  | { status: "idle" }
  | { status: "loading" }
  | { status: "success"; data: User[] }
  | { status: "error"; error: string };

const [state, setState] = useState<ComponentState>({ status: "idle" });

// TypeScript knows exactly what properties exist
if (state.status === "success") {
  console.log(state.data); // ✅ Type-safe
  console.log(state.error); // ❌ Error: 'error' doesn't exist on success
}
```

No more checking if `data` exists TypeScript handles it.

---

## 5. Make Event Handlers Type-Safe

Inline event typing is verbose. Extract them:

```typescript
// ❌ Messy and repetitive
<input onChange={(e: React.ChangeEvent<HTMLInputElement>) => {}} />

// ✅ Clean and reusable
const handleChange = (e: React.ChangeEvent<HTMLInputElement>) => {
  setValue(e.target.value);
};

<input onChange={handleChange} />
```

For form submissions:

```typescript
const handleSubmit = (e: React.FormEvent<HTMLFormElement>) => {
  e.preventDefault();
  // Type-safe form handling
};
```

---

## 6. Leverage Type Inference

TypeScript is smart. Don't annotate everything:

```typescript
// ✅ Unnecessary - TypeScript infers string[]
const [items, setItems] = useState<string[]>([]);

// ✅ Perfect - TypeScript still knows it's string[]
const [items, setItems] = useState([]);
```

Annotate only when inference fails or for complex types.

---

## 7. Create Reusable Generic Components

Generic components adapt to different types while staying type-safe:

```typescript
interface ListProps<T> {
  items: T[];
  renderItem: (item: T) => React.ReactNode;
}

function List<T>({ items, renderItem }: ListProps<T>) {
  return <ul>{items.map(renderItem)}</ul>;
}

// Usage with type inference
<List
  items={users} // TypeScript knows users is User[]
  renderItem={(user) => <li>{user.name}</li>}
/>
```

The component works with users, products, todos anything while maintaining type safety.

---

## 8. Extract Shared Types

Don't repeat yourself. Extract common types:

```typescript
// types/api.ts
export interface User {
  id: string;
  email: string;
  name: string;
  role: "admin" | "user";
}

// components/UserProfile.tsx
import { User } from "../types/api";

interface UserProfileProps {
  user: User;
  onUpdate: (user: User) => void;
}
```

One change updates everywhere. No hunting for duplicate interfaces.

---

## 9. Use satisfies for Complex Validations

TypeScript 4.9 introduced `satisfies` perfect for constants:

```typescript
const routes = {
  home: "/",
  profile: "/profile/:id",
  settings: "/settings",
} satisfies Record<string, string>;

// TypeScript checks that all values are strings
// But preserves the literal types for autocomplete
```

---

## What Changed After Adopting These

On a recent team project, implementing these practices reduced:

- **Runtime errors:** Down by 60%
- **Code review time:** Faster because TypeScript catches obvious mistakes
- **Onboarding time:** New devs understand component contracts instantly

---

## Key Takeaways

TypeScript isn't about "adding types" it's about removing entire categories of bugs before they happen.

Start with explicit props, embrace discriminated unions for state, and let inference work for you. Your future self (and your teammates) will thank you when refactoring isn't a nightmare.

The best TypeScript code is the code where the types fade into the background, quietly preventing mistakes while you focus on building features.

# useMemo and useCallback: When to Actually Use Them

I see it everywhere: every function wrapped in useCallback, every object in useMemo, just in case. "It's an optimization," they say.

But here's the uncomfortable truth: **misused memoization often hurts more than it helps.**

---

## The Cost of Memoization

Every useMemo and useCallback adds:

- Memory allocation for cached values
- Comparison logic on every render
- Complex dependency arrays to maintain
- Cognitive overhead for other developers

If the computation isn't expensive, you're slowing things down.

---

## When useMemo Actually Helps

**1. Expensive calculations**

```typescript
// ❌ Don't memoize simple math
const total = items.reduce((sum, i) => sum + i.price, 0);

// ✅ DO memoize heavy computations
const processedData = useMemo(() => {
  return hugeArray
    .filter((item) => item.complex)
    .map((item) => expensiveTransformation(item))
    .sort((a, b) => complexComparison(a, b));
}, [hugeArray]);
```

**2. Referential equality for dependencies**

```typescript
// Without memo: new object on every render = useEffect runs constantly
const config = useMemo(
  () => ({
    url: "/api/users",
    retries: 3,
    timeout: 5000,
  }),
  [],
); // Empty deps = stable reference

useEffect(() => {
  fetchData(config); // Only runs when config actually changes
}, [config]);
```

---

## When useCallback Actually Helps

**1. Passing callbacks to memoized children**

```typescript
const Child = React.memo(({ onClick }) => {
  console.log('Child rendered');
  return <button onClick={onClick}>Click</button>;
});

function Parent() {
  const [count, setCount] = useState(0);

  // Without useCallback: Child re-renders on every parent render
  const handleClick = useCallback(() => {
    console.log('Clicked');
  }, []); // Stable function reference

  return (
    <>
      <Child onClick={handleClick} />
      <button onClick={() => setCount(c + 1)}>Count: {count}</button>
    </>
  );
}
```

**2. useEffect dependencies**

```typescript
const fetchUser = useCallback(async (id: string) => {
  const response = await fetch(`/api/users/${id}`);
  return response.json();
}, []); // Stable reference

useEffect(() => {
  fetchUser(userId).then(setUser);
}, [fetchUser, userId]); // Won't trigger unnecessarily
```

---

## When to Skip Both

**1. Built-in DOM elements**

```typescript
// ❌ Waste of effort
const style = useMemo(() => ({ color: 'blue' }), []);
return <div style={style} />;

// ✅ Fine as is
return <div style={{ color: 'blue' }} />;
```

**2. Simple, cheap calculations**

```typescript
// ❌ Overkill
const doubled = useMemo(() => count * 2, [count]);

// ✅ Perfect
const doubled = count * 2;
```

**3. Event handlers on non-memoized components**

```typescript
// ❌ Child isn't memoized anyway
const handleClick = useCallback(() => {}, []);

// ✅ Regular function is fine
const handleClick = () => {};
```

---

## The Real Rules

| Situation                          | Use Memoization? |
| ---------------------------------- | ---------------- |
| Heavy computation (>1ms)           | ✅ Yes           |
| Object/array dependency for hooks  | ✅ Yes           |
| Function passed to memoized child  | ✅ Yes           |
| Simple arithmetic                  | ❌ No            |
| Inline styles                      | ❌ No            |
| Functions on non-memoized children | ❌ No            |

---

## Measure First, Optimize Second

```typescript
// Before adding memoization
console.time("expensive op");
const result = expensiveFunction(data);
console.timeEnd("expensive op"); // If >1ms, consider useMemo

// After adding
const result = useMemo(() => expensiveFunction(data), [data]);
```

---

## Key Takeaways

1. **Memoization has costs** it's not free
2. **Use it for referential stability**, not just performance
3. **Measure before optimizing** you might be surprised
4. **Default to normal code**, reach for hooks when needed

The best code isn't the most optimized it's the most maintainable. Optimize only when you have data that proves it matters.

---

# Web Workers in React: Offloading Heavy Computations

Your UI freezes. The user types, but nothing happens for seconds. They refresh. They leave.

The culprit? Heavy JavaScript blocking the main thread.

---

## <div>The Problem:</div> Blocking the UI Thread

```typescript
const DataProcessor = ({ data }: { data: number[] }) => {
  const processData = () => {
    // This blocks the UI for seconds
    const result = data
      .flatMap(expensiveTransform)
      .filter(complexFilter)
      .reduce(slowAggregation, {});
      
    setProcessedResult(result);
  };

  return (
    <button onClick={processData}>
      Process 100k items
    </button>
  );
};
```

While processing runs, the user can't type, scroll, or click anything.

---

## <div>The Solution:</div> Web Workers

Web Workers run code in a separate thread. UI stays responsive.

```typescript
// worker.ts - runs in background thread
self.addEventListener('message', (e: MessageEvent<number[]>) => {
  const data = e.data;
  
  // Heavy computation here
  const result = data
    .flatMap(expensiveTransform)
    .filter(complexFilter)
    .reduce(slowAggregation, {});
  
  // Send result back
  self.postMessage(result);
});
```

---

## Type-Safe Worker with Comlink

```bash
npm install comlink
```

Comlink makes worker communication feel like regular function calls:

```typescript
// worker.ts
import { expose } from 'comlink';

const api = {
  processData: (data: number[]) => {
    return data
      .flatMap(expensiveTransform)
      .filter(complexFilter)
      .reduce(slowAggregation, {});
  },
  
  generateReport: (users: User[]) => {
    return users.map(complexReportGeneration);
  }
};

export type WorkerAPI = typeof api;

expose(api);
```

---

## React Hook for Workers

```typescript
import { useEffect, useRef, useState } from 'react';
import { wrap, Remote } from 'comlink';
import type { WorkerAPI } from './worker';

export function useWorker<T = never>() {
  const [workerApi, setWorkerApi] = useState<Remote<WorkerAPI> | null>(null);
  const [isReady, setIsReady] = useState(false);
  const [error, setError] = useState<Error | null>(null);

  useEffect(() => {
    const initWorker = async () => {
      try {
        const worker = new Worker(
          new URL('./worker.ts', import.meta.url), 
          { type: 'module' }
        );
        
        const api = wrap<WorkerAPI>(worker);
        setWorkerApi(api);
        setIsReady(true);
      } catch (err) {
        setError(err instanceof Error ? err : new Error('Worker failed'));
      }
    };

    initWorker();

    return () => {
      // Cleanup worker
      if (workerApi) {
        workerApi[Symbol.dispose]?.();
      }
    };
  }, []);

  return { workerApi, isReady, error };
}
```

---

## Using the Worker Hook

```typescript
import { useState } from 'react';
import { useWorker } from './useWorker';

const DataProcessor = () => {
  const [result, setResult] = useState(null);
  const [isProcessing, setIsProcessing] = useState(false);
  const { workerApi, isReady, error } = useWorker();

  const handleProcess = async () => {
    if (!workerApi) return;
    
    setIsProcessing(true);
    try {
      const data = generateLargeDataset(); // 100k+ items
      
      // This runs in the worker - UI stays responsive
      const processed = await workerApi.processData(data);
      
      setResult(processed);
    } catch (err) {
      console.error('Processing failed:', err);
    } finally {
      setIsProcessing(false);
    }
  };

  if (error) return <div>Worker failed: {error.message}</div>;
  if (!isReady) return <div>Loading worker...</div>;

  return (
    <div>
      <button 
        onClick={handleProcess}
        disabled={isProcessing}
      >
        {isProcessing ? 'Processing...' : 'Process Data'}
      </button>
      
      {result && <pre>{JSON.stringify(result, null, 2)}</pre>}
    </div>
  );
};
```

---

## Real-World Examples

**1. Image Processing**

```typescript
// Worker
const applyFilters = (imageData: ImageData, filters: Filter[]) => {
  // Pixel manipulation - heavy work
  return processedImageData;
};

// Component
const { workerApi } = useWorker();
const result = await workerApi.applyFilters(imageData, selectedFilters);
```

**2. CSV/JSON Parsing**

```typescript
// Worker
const parseLargeCSV = (csvText: string) => {
  const lines = csvText.split('\n');
  // Parse 100k+ rows
  return parsedData;
};
```

**3. Data Visualization Calculations**

```typescript
// Worker
const calculateChartData = (rawData: DataPoint[]) => {
  // Aggregations, transformations, statistics
  return chartReadyData;
};
```

---

## Fallback Strategy

```typescript
const useHeavyComputation = <T, R>(
  fn: (data: T) => R,
  data: T
): R | null => {
  const [result, setResult] = useState<R | null>(null);
  const { workerApi, isReady } = useWorker();

  useEffect(() => {
    const compute = async () => {
      if (isReady && workerApi) {
        // Use worker if available
        const res = await workerApi.compute(fn, data);
        setResult(res);
      } else {
        // Fallback to main thread
        setResult(fn(data));
      }
    };
    
    compute();
  }, [data, isReady, workerApi]);

  return result;
};
```

---

## Performance Impact

| Operation | Main Thread | Web Worker |
|-----------|-------------|------------|
| 50k items processed | UI freezes for 3s | UI stays smooth |
| Image filter | 2s freeze | No lag |
| CSV parse | 5s freeze | Responsive |
| User interaction | Blocked | Works perfectly |

---

## Key Takeaways

1. **Web Workers keep UI responsive** during heavy computations
2. **Comlink makes worker communication feel native**
3. **Always provide fallbacks** for older browsers
4. **Clean up workers** when components unmount
5. **Measure before optimizing** only use workers for truly heavy work

Your users don't care about your complex calculations. They care about typing without lag.

---

# WebSockets in React: Building Real-Time Features with TypeScript

Users don't want to refresh pages anymore. They expect data to appear instantly new messages, live prices, updated scores.

HTTP polling works but wastes resources. WebSockets give you a persistent connection where data flows both ways instantly.

---

## What Makes WebSockets Different?

With regular HTTP, the client asks and the server answers. End of conversation.

With WebSockets, you open a connection once. Both sides can send messages anytime. No repeated handshakes. No waiting.

This makes them perfect for:

- Chat applications
- Live dashboards
- Collaborative editing
- Real-time notifications
- Gaming

---

## The Basic WebSocket API

The browser provides a native WebSocket object. It's simple but low-level:

```typescript
const socket = new WebSocket("wss://api.example.com/ws");

socket.onopen = () => {
  console.log("Connected");
  socket.send(JSON.stringify({ type: "join", room: "general" }));
};

socket.onmessage = (event) => {
  const data = JSON.parse(event.data);
  console.log("Received:", data);
};

socket.onclose = () => console.log("Disconnected");
socket.onerror = (error) => console.error("Error:", error);
```

The challenge in React is managing the connection lifecycle connecting when needed, cleaning up when not, and handling reconnection.

---

## Building a Reusable WebSocket Hook

Here's a custom hook that handles connection management:

```typescript
import { useEffect, useRef, useState, useCallback } from "react";

interface WebSocketConfig {
  url: string;
  onMessage?: <T>(data: T) => void;
  reconnectAttempts?: number;
  reconnectInterval?: number;
}

export function useWebSocket<T = unknown>({
  url,
  onMessage,
  reconnectAttempts = 5,
  reconnectInterval = 3000,
}: WebSocketConfig) {
  const [isConnected, setIsConnected] = useState(false);
  const [lastMessage, setLastMessage] = useState<T | null>(null);
  const socketRef = useRef<WebSocket | null>(null);
  const reconnectCountRef = useRef(0);
  const reconnectTimerRef = useRef<number>();

  const connect = useCallback(() => {
    socketRef.current = new WebSocket(url);

    socketRef.current.onopen = () => {
      setIsConnected(true);
      reconnectCountRef.current = 0;
      console.log("WebSocket connected");
    };

    socketRef.current.onclose = () => {
      setIsConnected(false);

      // Attempt reconnection
      if (reconnectCountRef.current < reconnectAttempts) {
        reconnectTimerRef.current = window.setTimeout(() => {
          reconnectCountRef.current++;
          connect();
        }, reconnectInterval);
      }
    };

    socketRef.current.onerror = (error) => {
      console.error("WebSocket error:", error);
    };

    socketRef.current.onmessage = (event) => {
      try {
        const data = JSON.parse(event.data) as T;
        setLastMessage(data);
        onMessage?.(data);
      } catch (error) {
        console.error("Failed to parse message:", error);
      }
    };
  }, [url, reconnectAttempts, reconnectInterval, onMessage]);

  useEffect(() => {
    connect();

    return () => {
      socketRef.current?.close();
      clearTimeout(reconnectTimerRef.current);
    };
  }, [connect]);

  const sendMessage = useCallback((data: unknown) => {
    if (socketRef.current?.readyState === WebSocket.OPEN) {
      socketRef.current.send(JSON.stringify(data));
    } else {
      console.warn("WebSocket not connected");
    }
  }, []);

  return { isConnected, lastMessage, sendMessage };
}
```

This hook handles reconnection automatically and cleans up when your component unmounts.

---

## Building a Chat Application

Let's build a simple chat to see WebSockets in action:

```typescript
interface ChatMessage {
  id: string;
  username: string;
  text: string;
  timestamp: number;
}

const ChatRoom = ({ roomId, username }: { roomId: string; username: string }) => {
  const [messages, setMessages] = useState<ChatMessage[]>([]);
  const [inputText, setInputText] = useState('');
  const messagesEndRef = useRef<HTMLDivElement>(null);

  const { isConnected, lastMessage, sendMessage } = useWebSocket<ChatMessage>({
    url: `wss://chat.example.com/rooms/${roomId}`,
    onMessage: (message) => {
      setMessages(prev => [...prev, message]);
    }
  });

  // Auto-scroll to latest message
  useEffect(() => {
    messagesEndRef.current?.scrollIntoView({ behavior: 'smooth' });
  }, [messages]);

  const handleSend = () => {
    if (!inputText.trim()) return;

    const message: ChatMessage = {
      id: crypto.randomUUID(),
      username,
      text: inputText,
      timestamp: Date.now()
    };

    sendMessage(message);
    setInputText('');
  };

  return (
    <div className="flex flex-col h-screen max-w-2xl mx-auto p-4">
      {/* Connection status */}
      <div className="flex items-center gap-2 mb-4">
        <div className={`w-2 h-2 rounded-full ${isConnected ? 'bg-green-500' : 'bg-red-500'}`} />
        <span>{isConnected ? 'Connected' : 'Reconnecting...'}</span>
      </div>

      {/* Messages */}
      <div className="flex-1 overflow-y-auto border rounded-lg p-4 mb-4">
        {messages.map(msg => (
          <div
            key={msg.id}
            className={`mb-2 ${msg.username === username ? 'text-right' : ''}`}
          >
            <div className={`inline-block max-w-xs p-2 rounded-lg ${
              msg.username === username
                ? 'bg-blue-500 text-white'
                : 'bg-gray-200'
            }`}>
              {msg.username !== username && (
                <div className="text-xs font-bold">{msg.username}</div>
              )}
              <div>{msg.text}</div>
              <div className="text-xs opacity-75">
                {new Date(msg.timestamp).toLocaleTimeString()}
              </div>
            </div>
          </div>
        ))}
        <div ref={messagesEndRef} />
      </div>

      {/* Input */}
      <div className="flex gap-2">
        <input
          type="text"
          value={inputText}
          onChange={(e) => setInputText(e.target.value)}
          onKeyPress={(e) => e.key === 'Enter' && handleSend()}
          className="flex-1 border rounded-lg px-3 py-2"
          placeholder="Type a message..."
        />
        <button
          onClick={handleSend}
          disabled={!isConnected}
          className="px-4 py-2 bg-blue-500 text-white rounded-lg disabled:opacity-50"
        >
          Send
        </button>
      </div>
    </div>
  );
};
```

